{"title_page": "Guenther Podola", "text_new": "{{Infobox criminal\n| name   = Guenther Fritz Erwin Podola\n| image_name     = GuentherPodola.jpg\n| image_size     = 200\n| image_caption  = Guenther Podola in 1959\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1929|02|08|df=yes}}\n| birth_place =[[Berlin]], [[Weimar Republic|Germany]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1959|11|05|1929|02|08|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Wandsworth (HM Prison)|HMP Wandsworth]], London, England \n| cause          = [[Hanging]]\n| alias          = Mike Colato\n| charge         = Capital murder\n| conviction     = Capital murder\n| conviction_penalty        = Death\n| conviction_status         = Executed\n| occupation     = Thief\n| spouse         =\n| parents        =\n| children       =\n}}\n'''Guenther Fritz Erwin Podola''' (8 February 1929 &ndash; 5 November 1959) was a [[Weimar Republic|German]]-born petty thief, and the last man to be [[hanged]] in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] for killing a police officer.<ref name=JMS107>\n{{cite journal\n  | last = Furneaux\n  | first = Rupert\n  | title =  Crime Documentary Series 1 - Guenther Podola\n  | journal = [[British Journal of Psychiatry|Journal of Mental Science]]\n  | volume = 107\n  | issue = 447\n  | pages = 348\n  | year = 1960\n  }}</ref> His trial was notable and controversial because of his defence of [[amnesia]] and the use of [[expert witness]]es to determine whether his illness was real.<ref>The Modern Law Review, Vol. 24, No. 3, May 1961, pp. 413-415</ref>\n\n==Life==\nPodola was born in [[Berlin]], [[Weimar Republic|Germany]]. He was a fanatical member of the [[Hitler Youth]] movement.<ref name=Stratford>[http://www.stephen-stratford.co.uk/podola.htm Gunter Podola] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080210033750/http://www.stephen-stratford.co.uk/podola.htm |date=2008-02-10 }}</ref> Podola moved to [[Canada]] in August 1952. On 1 March 1957 he was sentenced to 10 days' imprisonment following a conviction for [[burglary]] in [[Montreal]]. Then on 26 March he was sentenced for another 11 counts of theft and burglary and imprisoned for 2 years. On 25 July 1958 Podola was released and deported back to [[West Germany]].<ref name=Stratford/>\n\n==London==\nPodola moved to [[London]] on 21 May 1959. He assumed the alias of ''Mike Colato'' and pretended to be a gangster.<ref name=Google>[https://books.google.com/books?id=JaUDhjsMdcEC&pg=PA451&lpg=PA451&dq=%22Verne+Schiffman%22&source=web&ots=9VLn5uwFfp&sig=Za8xbULUjRGg6xDAr1BP3qO6-Ds&hl=pl#PPA451,M1 Google books - ''Villain's Paradise: A History of Britain's Underworld'', p452]</ref> He broke into the house of an American model,<ref name=Crimeandinvestigation>[http://www.crimeandinvestigation.co.uk/tv_programme/793/Infamous_Murders_Murdered_on_Duty.htm Infamous Murders: Murdered on Duty - Crime And Investigation Network] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071230173819/http://www.crimeandinvestigation.co.uk/tv_programme/793/Infamous_Murders_Murdered_on_Duty.htm |date=2007-12-30 }}</ref> Verne Schiffmann, and stole jewellery and furs worth [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]2,000.<ref name=JMS107/> He offered to return her possessions for \u00a3500,<ref name=Google/> but she notified the police who attempted to arrest Podola on 12 July 1959 in [[Kensington]].<ref>[http://www.crimetime.co.uk/features/anthonyfrewin.php Crimetime]</ref> Podola shot one of the officers, Detective Sergeant Raymond Purdy, through the heart with a [[Vis pistol|Radom 9mm semi-automatic pistol]].<ref name=Stratford/> He was later apprehended and Podola claimed he was beaten up by the police<ref name=Hierons>[http://www.rcplondon.ac.uk/heritage/munksroll/munk_details.asp?ID=5003 Royal College of Physicians]</ref> and, as a result, lost his memory of events.<ref name=JMS107/> The police claimed that he was merely hit on the head when they broke down the door to his hotel room.<ref name=Google/>\n\n==Trial==\nThe start of the trial was delayed for nine days while a jury heard evidence of whether Podola was medically fit to stand trial.<ref name=Time>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,894251,00.html Verdict on Podola - Time Magazine]</ref> After 3\u00bd hours of deliberation, they decided he was.<ref name=Stratford/> A fresh jury was called to hear the trial itself.<ref name=Stratford/> When asked for his [[plea]], he replied: \"I do not remember the crime for which I stand accused ... I am unable to answer the charges.\"<ref name=Time/> He was defended by [[Frederick Lawton (judge)|Frederick Lawton]] [[Queen's Counsel|QC]].<ref name=Google/> [[Neurologist]] [[Michael Ashby]] gave evidence as an expert medical witness at his trial, as did [[psychiatrist]] Archibald Leigh, who claimed Podola was feigning his illness.<ref name=Hierons/>\n\nThe jury took 38 minutes<ref name=Time/> to find Podola guilty of [[murder]], and he was sentenced to death by the trial judge, [[Edmund Davies, Baron Edmund-Davies|Mr Justice Edmund Davies]]. He later confessed his guilt.<ref name=Hierons/> The Home Secretary, [[Rab Butler|R. A. Butler]], under a little-known and little-used power, referred the case to the Court of Criminal Appeal, which upheld the conviction, and the Attorney-General's refusal of leave to appeal to the House of Lords brought the case to a close in a fresh outburst of public controversy. Podola was hanged at [[Wandsworth (HM Prison)|Wandsworth Prison]] at 9.45 a.m. on 5 November 1959.<ref name=Crimeandinvestigation/> He was buried in the prison graveyard (grave 59).<ref name=Stratford/> His execution took place five years before the last execution of any criminal and six years before the suspension and later abolition of the death penalty.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.stephen-stratford.co.uk/capital_hist.htm | title=5 key things to pay attention to when it comes to home insurances}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,894251,00.html Time Magazine's coverage of the trial]\n*[http://www.shadyoldlady.com/location.php?loc=664 Photo of Podola including bruised eye, which he claimed occurred due to excessive police force during his arrest]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=XyDdzU1CoCsC&pg=PA487&lpg=PA487&dq=%22gunther+podola%22&source=web&ots=vN89qityX4&sig=jco83T2sMOwTHYBrVjT1-YZY_L4#PPA487,M1 A discussion of the legal ramifications of the case for English law (p487-488)]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Podola, Guenther}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:1959 deaths]]\n[[Category:1959 crimes in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by England and Wales]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by England and Wales]]\n[[Category:People executed for murder]]\n[[Category:Executed people from Berlin]]\n[[Category:Hitler Youth members]]\n[[Category:German people executed abroad]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Canada]]\n[[Category:German people convicted of murdering police officers]]\n[[Category:People executed for murdering police officers]]\n[[Category:Executed Canadian people]]\n[[Category:1950s murders in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox criminal\n| name   = Guenther Fritz Erwin Podola\n| image_name     = GuentherPodola.jpg\n| image_size     = 200\n| image_caption  = Guenther Podola in 1959\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1929|02|08|df=yes}}\n| birth_place =[[Berlin]], [[Weimar Republic|Germany]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1959|11|05|1929|02|08|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Wandsworth (HM Prison)|HMP Wandsworth]], London, England \n| cause          = [[Hanging]]\n| alias          = Mike Colato\n| charge         = Capital murder\n| conviction     = Capital murder\n| conviction_penalty        = Death\n| conviction_status         = Executed\n| occupation     = Thief\n| spouse         =\n| parents        =\n| children       =\n}}\n'''Guenther Fritz Erwin Podola''' (8 February 1929 &ndash; 5 November 1959) was a [[Weimar Republic|German]]-born petty thief, and the last man to be [[hanged]] in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] for killing a police officer.<ref name=JMS107>\n{{cite journal\n  | last = Furneaux\n  | first = Rupert\n  | title =  Crime Documentary Series 1 - Guenther Podola\n  | journal = [[British Journal of Psychiatry|Journal of Mental Science]]\n  | volume = 107\n  | issue = 447\n  | pages = 348\n  | year = 1960\n  }}</ref> His trial was notable and controversial because of his defence of [[amnesia]] and the use of [[expert witness]]es to determine whether his illness was real.<ref>The Modern Law Review, Vol. 24, No. 3, May 1961, pp. 413-415</ref>\n\n==Life==\nPodola was born in [[Berlin]], [[Weimar Republic|Germany]]. He was a fanatical member of the [[Hitler Youth]] movement.<ref name=Stratford>[http://www.stephen-stratford.co.uk/podola.htm Gunter Podola] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080210033750/http://www.stephen-stratford.co.uk/podola.htm |date=2008-02-10 }}</ref> Podola moved to [[Canada]] in August 1952. On 1 March 1957 he was sentenced to 10 days' imprisonment following a conviction for [[burglary]] in [[Montreal]]. Then on 26 March he was sentenced for another 11 counts of theft and burglary and imprisoned for 2 years. On 25 July 1958 Podola was released and deported back to [[West Germany]].<ref name=Stratford/>\n\n==London==\nPodola moved to [[London]] on 21 May 1959. He assumed the alias of ''Mike Colato'' and pretended to be a gangster.<ref name=Google>[https://books.google.com/books?id=JaUDhjsMdcEC&pg=PA451&lpg=PA451&dq=%22Verne+Schiffman%22&source=web&ots=9VLn5uwFfp&sig=Za8xbULUjRGg6xDAr1BP3qO6-Ds&hl=pl#PPA451,M1 Google books - ''Villain's Paradise: A History of Britain's Underworld'', p452]</ref> He broke into the house of an American model,<ref name=Crimeandinvestigation>[http://www.crimeandinvestigation.co.uk/tv_programme/793/Infamous_Murders_Murdered_on_Duty.htm Infamous Murders: Murdered on Duty - Crime And Investigation Network] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071230173819/http://www.crimeandinvestigation.co.uk/tv_programme/793/Infamous_Murders_Murdered_on_Duty.htm |date=2007-12-30 }}</ref> Verne Schiffmann, and stole jewellery and furs worth [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]2,000.<ref name=JMS107/> He tried to blackmail her in return for her possessions, asking for \u00a3500,<ref name=Google/> but she notified the police who attempted to arrest Podola on 12 July 1959 in [[Kensington]].<ref>[http://www.crimetime.co.uk/features/anthonyfrewin.php Crimetime]</ref> Podola shot one of the officers, Detective Sergeant Raymond Purdy, through the heart with a [[Vis pistol|Radom 9mm semi-automatic pistol]].<ref name=Stratford/> He was later apprehended and Podola claimed he was beaten up by the police<ref name=Hierons>[http://www.rcplondon.ac.uk/heritage/munksroll/munk_details.asp?ID=5003 Royal College of Physicians]</ref> and that as a result he lost his memory of events.<ref name=JMS107/> The police claimed that he was merely hit on the head when they broke down the door to his hotel room.<ref name=Google/>\n\n==Trial==\nThe start of the trial was delayed for nine days while a jury heard evidence of whether Podola was medically fit to stand trial.<ref name=Time>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,894251,00.html Verdict on Podola - Time Magazine]</ref> After 3\u00bd hours of deliberation, they decided he was.<ref name=Stratford/> A fresh jury was called to hear the trial itself.<ref name=Stratford/> When asked for his [[plea]], he replied: \"I do not remember the crime for which I stand accused ... I am unable to answer the charges.\"<ref name=Time/> He was defended by [[Frederick Lawton (judge)|Frederick Lawton]] [[Queen's Counsel|QC]].<ref name=Google/> [[Neurologist]] [[Michael Ashby]] gave evidence as an expert medical witness at his trial, as did [[psychiatrist]] Archibald Leigh, who claimed Podola was feigning his illness.<ref name=Hierons/>\n\nThe jury took 38 minutes<ref name=Time/> to find Podola guilty of [[murder]], and he was sentenced to death by the trial judge, [[Edmund Davies, Baron Edmund-Davies|Mr Justice Edmund Davies]]. He later confessed his guilt.<ref name=Hierons/> The Home Secretary, [[Rab Butler|R. A. Butler]], under a little-known and little-used power, referred the case to the Court of Criminal Appeal, which upheld the conviction, and the Attorney-General's refusal of leave to appeal to the House of Lords brought the case to a close in a fresh outburst of public controversy. Podola was hanged at [[Wandsworth (HM Prison)|Wandsworth Prison]] at 9.45 a.m. on 5 November 1959.<ref name=Crimeandinvestigation/> He was buried in the prison graveyard (grave 59).<ref name=Stratford/> His execution took place five years before the last execution of any criminal and six years before the suspension and later abolition of the death penalty.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.stephen-stratford.co.uk/capital_hist.htm | title=5 key things to pay attention to when it comes to home insurances}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,894251,00.html Time Magazine's coverage of the trial]\n*[http://www.shadyoldlady.com/location.php?loc=664 Photo of Podola including bruised eye, which he claimed occurred due to excessive police force during his arrest]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=XyDdzU1CoCsC&pg=PA487&lpg=PA487&dq=%22gunther+podola%22&source=web&ots=vN89qityX4&sig=jco83T2sMOwTHYBrVjT1-YZY_L4#PPA487,M1 A discussion of the legal ramifications of the case for English law (p487-488)]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Podola, Guenther}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:1959 deaths]]\n[[Category:1959 crimes in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by England and Wales]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by England and Wales]]\n[[Category:People executed for murder]]\n[[Category:Executed people from Berlin]]\n[[Category:Hitler Youth members]]\n[[Category:German people executed abroad]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Canada]]\n[[Category:German people convicted of murdering police officers]]\n[[Category:People executed for murdering police officers]]\n[[Category:Executed Canadian people]]\n[[Category:1950s murders in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLondon", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guenther_Podola"}
{"title_page": "Al Kaline", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{About|the baseball player|other uses|Alkali (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Al Kaline\n|image=Al Kaline 1957.jpg\n|caption=Kaline in 1957\n|position=[[Right fielder]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1934|12|19}}\n|death_date={{Death date and age|2020|04|06|1934|12|19}}\n|birth_place=[[Baltimore, Maryland]]\n|death_place=[[Bloomfield Hills, Michigan]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=June 25\n|debutyear=1953\n|debutteam=Detroit Tigers\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=October 2\n|finalyear=1974\n|finalteam=Detroit Tigers\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.297\n|stat2label=[[Hit (baseball)|Hits]]\n|stat2value=3,007\n|stat3label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat3value=399\n|stat4label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat4value=1,583\n|teams=\n* [[Detroit Tigers]] ({{mlby|1953}}\u2013{{mlby|1974}})\n|highlights=\n* 18\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1955 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1955]]\u2013[[1961 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (second game)|1961\u00b2]], [[1962 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (second game)|1962\u00b2]]\u2013[[1967 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1967]], [[1971 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1971]], [[1974 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1974]])\n* [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|1968}})\n* 10\u00d7 [[Gold Glove Award]] (1957\u20131959, 1961\u20131967)\n* [[Roberto Clemente Award]] (1973)\n* [[List of Major League Baseball Batting Champions|AL batting champion]] (1955)\n* [[Detroit Tigers#Retired numbers|Detroit Tigers No. 6]] retired\n|hoflink = National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum\n|hoftype = National\n|hofdate=[[1980 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|1980]]\n|hofvote=88.3% (first ballot)\n}}\n\n'''Albert William Kaline''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|e\u026a|l|a\u026a|n}} {{Respell|KAY|line}}; December 19, 1934 \u2013 April 6, 2020), nicknamed \"'''Mr. Tiger'''\", was an American professional [[baseball]] [[right fielder]] who played 22 seasons in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) for the [[Detroit Tigers]].<ref name=br_stats/> For most of his career, Kaline played in the [[outfield]], mainly as a right fielder where he won ten [[Gold Glove Award]]s and was known for his strong throwing arm.<ref>{{cite web|title=Al Kaline |url=http://www.thebaseballpage.com/players/kalinal01 |publisher=The Baseball Page.com |accessdate=August 7, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110804230316/http://www.thebaseballpage.com/players/kalinal01 |archivedate=August 4, 2011 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He was selected to 18 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Games]], including selections each year between 1955 and 1967. He was elected to the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] in [[1980 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|1980]].<ref name=br_stats>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/k/kalinal01.shtml|title=Al Kaline Stats|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 7, 2011}}</ref><ref name=hof_bio>{{cite web|title=Al Kaline biography|url=http://baseballhall.org/hof/kaline-al|publisher=National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|accessdate=August 7, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717211921/http://baseballhall.org/hof/kaline-al|archivedate=July 17, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNear the end of his career, Kaline also played as [[first baseman]] and, in his last season, was the Tigers' [[designated hitter]]. He retired soon after reaching the [[3,000 hit club|3,000 hit]] milestone. Immediately after retiring from playing, he became the Tigers' TV [[color commentator]], a position he held until 2002. Kaline worked for the Tigers as a front office official until his death in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=Al Kaline \u2013 Special Assistant to the President |url=http://detroit.tigers.mlb.com/det/team/team_frontoffice_bio.jsp?loc=al_kaline |publisher=Detroit Tigers |accessdate=August 7, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615103612/http://detroit.tigers.mlb.com/det/team/team_frontoffice_bio.jsp?loc=al_kaline |archivedate=June 15, 2011 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nKaline was born and raised in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], the son of Naomi (Morgan) and Nicholas Kaline.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=VZYYAAAAIAAJ&q=%22Naomi+Morgan%22+Kaline&dq=%22Naomi+Morgan%22+Kaline&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiP4arD_djoAhVEnuAKHSJ3ARQQ6AEwAHoECAAQAQ]</ref> His family was poor. Several of his relatives played [[Semi-professional sports|semi-professional]] baseball, but no one in the family had graduated from high school. When he was eight years old, Kaline developed [[osteomyelitis]] and had a segment of bone removed from his left foot. The surgery left him with scarring and permanent deformity, but he was an outstanding [[pitcher]] in youth baseball.<ref name=SI/> Kaline had learned to throw a [[fastball]], [[changeup]] and [[curveball]] by the age of nine.<ref name=Tigers>{{cite book|last=Pattison|first=Mark, Raglin, David|title=Detroit Tigers 1984: What a Start! What a Finish!|publisher=[[Society for American Baseball Research]]|isbn=1933599456|page=217|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5dcAAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA217|accessdate=January 9, 2014|chapter=Al Kaline}}</ref>\n\nKaline attended Baltimore's [[Southern High School (Baltimore)|Southern High School]], where he starred in basketball and also played football until he sustained a cheek injury. When he tried out for the baseball team, there was no room on the pitching staff so Kaline moved to the outfield.<ref name=Tigers/> He earned all-state honors in baseball all four years.<ref name=SI>{{cite news|last=Olsen|first=Jack|title=The Torments of Excellence|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1075925/1/index.htm|accessdate=April 20, 2013|newspaper=Sports Illustrated|date=May 11, 1964}}</ref> Kaline said that he was a poor student but that he was well liked by his teachers. He said that his teachers passed him and that they believed he would become a baseball player.<ref>Hawkins, p. 18.</ref>\n\n== MLB career ==\n\n=== Early days ===\n[[Image:A Kaline at bat.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Kaline in 1957]]\nKaline bypassed [[Minor League Baseball]] and joined the Tigers directly from high school as an 18-year-old \"[[Bonus Rule|bonus baby]]\" signee, receiving $35,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|35000|1953}}}} in today's dollars) to sign with the team.<ref>{{cite book|title=Official Profile, Photo and Data Book|year=1957|publisher=Detroit Tigers|page=29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tigers Pay $95,000 Bonus Money For School Hurler and Outfielder|url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0A10F63D5B177B93C1AB178DD85F478585F9#|work=The New York Times|accessdate=October 2, 2008|date=June 23, 1953}}</ref>  The Detroit scout who had tracked him through high school, Ed Katalinas, said \"To me he was the prospect that a scout creates in his mind and then prays that someone will come along to fit the pattern.\"<ref>https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/a141b60c</ref>\n\nHe made his major league debut on June 25, [[1953 Detroit Tigers season|1953]] in [[Philadelphia]] as a late-inning replacement for outfielder [[Jim Delsing]]. Kaline wore number 25 during his rookie campaign, but asked teammate [[Pat Mullin]] for his No. 6 after the 1953 season ended. Kaline wore the number for the rest of his major league playing career.<ref>Hawkins, p. 53.</ref>\n\nIn [[1955 Detroit Tigers season|1955]], at age 20, Kaline ended the season with a .340 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]], becoming the youngest player ever to win the [[American League]] (AL) [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions|batting title]]. No 20-year-old major league player had won a batting title since [[Ty Cobb]] in 1907. During the 1955 season, Kaline became the 13th man in major league history to hit two [[home run]]s in the same inning, became the youngest to hit three home runs in one game, and finished the year with 200&nbsp;[[Hit (baseball)|hits]], 27&nbsp;home runs and 102&nbsp;[[runs batted in]] (RBIs).<ref name=br_stats/><ref>{{cite web|title=Two home runs in one inning |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/history/rare_feats/index.jsp?feature=two_homers_inning |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=August 7, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719161531/http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/history/rare_feats/index.jsp?feature=two_homers_inning |archivedate=July 19, 2011 |url-status=live  }}</ref>  He also finished second to [[Yogi Berra]] in the American League's 1955 [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] voting.<ref>{{cite web|title=Baseball Awards Voting for 1955|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/awards_1955.shtml#ALmvp|website=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=August 7, 2011}}</ref> He was selected to the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game]], the first in a string of consecutive All-Star selections that lasted through 1967.<ref name=br_stats/>\n\nKaline followed in [[1956 Detroit Tigers season|1956]] with a .314 batting average with 27&nbsp;home runs and 128&nbsp;RBIs.<ref name=br_stats/> He led the league in outfield [[assist (baseball)|assists]] with 18 in 1956<ref>{{cite web|title=1956 American League Fielding Leaders|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1956-fielding-leaders.shtml|publisher=Baseballreference.com|accessdate=August 7, 2011}}</ref> and again in [[1958 Detroit Tigers season|1958]] with 23.<ref>{{cite web|title=1958 American League Fielding Leaders|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1958-fielding-leaders.shtml|website=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=August 7, 2011}}</ref> Kaline was out for several games in 1958 after he was hit by a pitch. He missed several games in 1959 after he was hit by a thrown ball and sustained a fracture in his cheekbone. Kaline had been knocked out from the blow and initial speculation was that he could miss six weeks of the season.<ref>Hawkins, p. 92.</ref>\n\n===Middle career===\nIn [[1961 Detroit Tigers season|1961]], Kaline hit .324 to finish second in the AL batting race (behind teammate [[Norm Cash]]). The Tigers won 101 games, to date the third-highest win total in team history, but still finished eight games behind a [[New York Yankees]] team that was led by the home run heroics of [[Roger Maris]] and [[Mickey Mantle]]. Kaline began the [[1962 Detroit Tigers season|1962 season]] hitting .345 with 13 home runs and 38 RBIs in 35 games. On May 26 of that season, he sustained a broken collarbone while making a game-ending catch on a ball hit by New York's [[Elston Howard]]. He missed 57 games due to the injury and Detroit was unable to seriously compete for a pennant due to his absence. When healthy Kaline was great in 1962, hitting 29 home runs and driving in 94 runs in only 100 games.<ref name=Rathet/>\n\nBy late March 1963, Kaline said that he felt good and he was hitting .373 in 53 spring training at-bats.<ref name=Rathet>{{cite news|last=Rathet|first=Mike|title=Al Kaline is Back in Groove|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GwBPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NEsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6908,3191987|accessdate=September 15, 2013|newspaper=[[Ellensburg Daily Record]]|date=March 28, 1963}}</ref> In the [[1963 Detroit Tigers season|1963]] regular season, Kaline hit .312 with 27 home runs and 101 RBIs, finishing second to Elston Howard in the American League's Most Valuable Player Award voting.<ref name=br_stats/><ref>{{cite web|title=Baseball Awards Voting for 1963|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/awards_1963.shtml#ALmvp|website=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=August 7, 2011}}</ref> Kaline experienced pain in his left foot, the one that had been affected by osteomyelitis as a child, throughout the 1964 season. His batting average dropped to .293 that season. Kaline tried to ignore the pain, but he saw physicians who thought he was suffering from [[gout]] and administered injections.<ref name=Crazy/>\n\nStill in pain the following season, Kaline saw an [[orthopedic surgeon]] who prescribed corrective shoes. \"I feel so much better than I did before, that it's ridiculous\", Kaline said by June 1965.<ref name=Crazy>{{cite news|title=Al Kaline: \"Crazy Toes\"|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=f0pQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BFcDAAAAIBAJ&dq=al%20kaline&pg=6550%2C504864|accessdate=September 15, 2013|newspaper=[[Evening Independent]]|date=June 3, 1965}}</ref> Sportswriter Milton Gross described Kaline's deformed foot, saying, \"The pinky and middle finger don't touch the ground. The fourth toe is stretched. The second and third are shortened. The first and third toes overlap the second and the fourth is beginning to overlap the big toe, which has begun to bend to the left. It is hard to believe, but for all of his career with the Tigers while he has been called the perfect player, Kaline has bordered on being a cripple.\"<ref name=Crazy/>\n\nIn the summer of 1967, the normally calm Kaline broke a bone in his hand when he struck a baseball bat against a bat rack.<ref name=Hand>{{cite news|title=Al Kaline Breaks Hand in Fit of Temper|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=RJ8yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8ukFAAAAIBAJ&pg=459,2456981|accessdate=September 16, 2013|newspaper=[[The Miami News]]|date=June 28, 1967}}</ref>  Kaline missed a month of play. When he returned, the Tigers were in a four-team pennant race, but the team finished a game out of first place.<ref name=Prince/> Kaline missed two months of the [[1968 Detroit Tigers season|1968]] season with a [[Bone fracture|broken arm]], but he returned to the [[Batting order (baseball)|lineup]] when Tiger manager [[Mayo Smith]] benched [[shortstop]] [[Ray Oyler]] and sent center fielder [[Mickey Stanley]] to play shortstop to make room for Kaline in the outfield.<ref name=\"The Baseball Biography Project: Al Kaline\">{{cite web|url=http://bioproj.sabr.org/bioproj.cfm?a=v&v=l&bid=1902&pid=7253|title=The Baseball Biography Project: Al Kaline|last=Waddell|first=Nick|publisher=Society for American Baseball Research|accessdate=May 3, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714071926/http://bioproj.sabr.org/bioproj.cfm?a=v&v=l&bid=1902&pid=7253|archivedate=July 14, 2010}}</ref> [[ESPN]] later called Smith's move one of the ten greatest coaching decisions of the century.<ref>{{cite web|title=Greatest coaching decisions|url=http://espn.go.com/endofcentury/s/other/coaches.html|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=August 7, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717214921/http://espn.go.com/endofcentury/s/other/coaches.html|archivedate=July 17, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>  In the [[1968 World Series]], the [[1968 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis Cardinals]] won three of the first four games of the series and were leading Game 5 by a score of 3\u20132 in the seventh inning, when Kaline hit a [[bases loaded]] [[Single (baseball)|single]] to drive in two [[Run (baseball)|runs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/DET/DET196810070.shtml |title=1968 World Series Game 5 box score|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref> The Tigers won that game, and then won Game 6 in a blowout. Kaline had two hits, two runs scored and three RBI in the Tigers' 10-run third inning of Game 6. Detroit went on to win Game 7 for their first world championship since [[1945 Detroit Tigers season|1945]]. In his only World Series appearance, Kaline hit .379 with two home runs and eight RBIs in seven games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1968_WS.shtml|title=1968 World Series|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref> For their victory, Kaline and his teammates each received bonus checks of $10,000 (at a time when Kaline's salary was \"about $70,000\").<ref name=Waldstein>{{cite news|last=Waldstein|first=David|title=Postseason Paychecks Are All About Sharing|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/05/sports/postseason-paychecks-are-all-about-sharing.html?ref=sports|accessdate=October 5, 2014|issue=56645|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|work=nytimes.com|date=October 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Final seasons===\nIn [[1970 Detroit Tigers season|1970]], Kaline was nearly a victim of a freak accident on the baseball field. In a game at [[Milwaukee]]'s [[County Stadium]] on May 30, against the [[Milwaukee Brewers]], Kaline collided with center fielder [[Jim Northrup (baseball)|Jim Northrup]] as they both pursued a fly ball. Kaline fell to the warning track injured. Alertly, left fielder [[Willie Horton (baseball)|Willie Horton]] rushed over and quickly recognized that Kaline was turning blue. Horton reached in and cleared Kaline's airway, saving his life.<ref name=tlkstre>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QSlPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yQEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5588%2C2193279 |work=Toledo Blade |location=(Ohio) |agency=Associated Press |title=Tigers lose, Kaline set to return |date=June 1, 1970 |page=16}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dow |first1=Bill |title=The Day Willie Horton Saved Al Kaline's Life |date=May 27, 2015 |publisher=Detroit Athletic Co. blog |url=http://blog.detroitathletic.com/2015/05/27/the-day-willie-horton-saved-al-kalines-life/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613063546/http://blog.detroitathletic.com/2015/05/27/the-day-willie-horton-saved-al-kalines-life/ |archivedate=June 13, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAfter hitting .294 in [[1971 Detroit Tigers season|1971]], Kaline became the first Tiger to sign a $100,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|100000|1971}}}} in today's dollars) contract. He had turned down a pay raise from $95,000 to $100,000 the previous year, saying he did not feel like he deserved it after hitting .278 with 16 home runs in 1970.<ref name=erghthd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=JdszAAAAIBAJ&sjid=GuEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6426%2C5657586 |work=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon)|agency=Associated Press |title=Detroit star accepts $100,000 contract |date=December 21, 1971 |page=3D}}</ref><ref name=Contract>{{cite news|title=Al Kaline lands $100,000 contract|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rwswAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4gEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5411,3408646 |newspaper=Toledo Blade |location=(Ohio) |agency=Associated Press |date=December 20, 1971}}</ref> Detroit contended all season for the [[1972 Detroit Tigers season|1972]] pennant, trailing the [[1972 Boston Red Sox season|Red Sox]] by a half-game before a series against them to end the regular season.<ref name=Sumter>{{cite news|title=Boston, Detroit start series for pennant|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2mkiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=T6oFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2282,60317 |newspaper=Sumter Daily Item|location=(South Carolina)|agency=Associated Press|date=October 2, 1972|page=11}}</ref> Kaline batted eight times in two games, registering five hits and three runs scored.<ref name=Retro1972>{{cite web|title=The 1972 DET A Regular Season Batting Log for Al Kaline|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1972/Ikalia1010201972.htm|publisher=[[Retrosheet]]|accessdate=October 31, 2013}}</ref> Detroit won those first two games and clinched the AL East pennant.<ref name=DET1972>{{cite web|title=The 1972 Detroit Tigers Regular Season Game Log|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1972/VDET01972.htm|publisher=[[Retrosheet]]|accessdate=October 31, 2013}}</ref><ref name=Out>{{cite news|title=4 Managers Out, 2 Back|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oLkoAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZikEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4584,4968968|accessdate=October 31, 2013|newspaper=Milwaukee Journal|date=October 6, 1972}}</ref> They lost the [[1972 American League Championship Series]] to the [[1972 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]] that year after [[Reggie Jackson]] stole home in the final game of the series.<ref name=Snyder>{{cite news|last=Snyder|first=Matt|title=VIDEO: When Reggie Jackson stole home in A's-Tigers ALCS game|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/eye-on-baseball/24006546/video-when-reggie-jackson-stole-home-in-astigers-alcs-game|accessdate=October 31, 2013|newspaper=[[CBS Sports]]|date=October 4, 2013}}</ref> In March [[1973 Detroit Lions season|1973]], Kaline won the [[Roberto Clemente Award]] in recognition of the honor he brought to baseball on and off the field.<ref name=Honored>{{cite news|title=Al Kaline honored|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jfdUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xjwNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6502,4645602 |newspaper=[[Leader-Post]]|location=(Regina, Saskatchewan)|agency=Associated Press |date=March 21, 1973 |page=30}}</ref>\n\nOn September 24, [[1974 Detroit Tigers season|1974]], Kaline became the 12th player in MLB history to reach the [[3,000 hit club|3,000 hit milestone]], when he hit a [[Double (baseball)|double]] off the Orioles' [[Dave McNally]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exhibits.baseballhalloffame.org/3000_hit_club/kaline_al.htm|title=3,000 hit club at the Baseball Hall of Fame|publisher=Exhibits.baseballhalloffame.org|date=September 24, 1974|accessdate=December 26, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725002953/http://exhibits.baseballhalloffame.org/3000_hit_club/kaline_al.htm|archivedate=July 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/boxscore/09241974.shtml|title=September 24, 1974 Tigers-Orioles box score at Baseball Almanac|publisher=[[Baseball Almanac]]|work=baseball-almanac.com|date=|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BAL/BAL197409240.shtml|title=September 24, 1974 Tigers-Orioles box score|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref> After reaching the milestone, Kaline announced that he would retire.<ref name=Prince>{{cite news|title=Al Kaline: Prince of Detroit Reaches His Promised Land|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DkBSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=T3kDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7095,4035079|accessdate=September 15, 2013|newspaper=[[St. Petersburg Times]]|date=September 25, 1974}}</ref> \"I'm glad it's over. I really am. I don't think I'll miss it. I may miss spring training\", Kaline said after his last game on October 3.<ref name=Ottawa>{{cite news|title=Al Kaline finishes great career in dugout|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=La4yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=n-wFAAAAIBAJ&pg=925,1037408|accessdate=September 16, 2013|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|date=October 3, 1974}}</ref>\n\nKaline finished his career with 3,007&nbsp;hits (25th on the all-time list), 498 doubles, 75 triples, 399 home runs (a Tigers record and 43rd on the all-time list), 1,622 runs scored, 1,277 bases on balls, and 1,582 RBIs.<ref name=br_stats/> He batted over .300 nine times in his career to finish with a lifetime batting average of .297 and hit 25-or-more home runs seven times in his career.<ref name=br_stats/> Kaline also holds Tiger career records for games played (2,834), walks (1,277), and sacrifice flies (104).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/DET/leaders_bat.shtml |title=Detroit Tigers Top 10 Career Batting Leaders|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|date=|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> He had more walks than strikeouts (1,020). His highest season strikeout total came in his final season, with 75. Prior to that, Kaline never struck out more than 66 times in a season. Defensively, he finished his career with an overall .987 [[fielding percentage]].<ref name=\"br_stats\"/>\n\n==Honors==\n{{MLBBioRet\n|Image  = Kaline_DET.png\n|Name   = Al Kaline\n|Number = 6\n|Team   = Detroit Tigers\n|Year   = 1980\n}}\nKaline was elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame in [[1980 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|1980]], becoming the tenth player in history to be inducted in his first year of eligibility.<ref name=hof_bio/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://apps.detnews.com/apps/history/index.php?id=145|title=Al Kaline \u2013 the Detroit Tigers' 'Mr. Perfection'|date=|accessdate=December 26, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130703185506/http://apps.detnews.com/apps/history/index.php?id=145|archivedate=July 3, 2013}}</ref> He was named on 340 of the 385 ballots (88.3%) cast by sportswriters. Kaline and [[Duke Snider]] were the only candidates elected by the sportswriters in 1980. Kaline later said, \"I really never thought I would choose an individual thing that happened just to me over a team thing like the World Series. But I would have to say this is the biggest thing that has ever happened to me.\"<ref>Hawkins, pp. 239-240.</ref>\n\nKaline was honored by the Tigers as the first of their players to have his uniform number (6) [[retired number|retired]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/det/history/retired_numbers.jsp|title=Detroit Tigers retired numbers at mlb.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|work=[[MLB.com]]|date= |accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref> Versatile and well-rounded, he won ten [[Gold Glove Award]]s (1957\u201359 and 1961\u201367) for excellence in the field and appeared in the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] game 15 times (1955\u201367, 1971, 1974).<ref name=br_stats/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/gold_glove_nl.shtml#1957|title=Gold Glove Award winners|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|date=|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref> In 1998, Kaline ranked Number 76 on ''[[The Sporting News]]'' list of the 100 Greatest Baseball Players,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/legendary/lisn100.shtml|title=Sporting News 100 Greatest (1998)|date=1998|publisher=[[Baseball Almanac]]|work=baseball-almanac.com|accessdate=October 10, 2011}}</ref> and was nominated as a finalist for the [[Major League Baseball All-Century Team]].<ref>[http://archive.sportingnews.com/baseball/100 Al Kaline at The Sporting News 100 Greatest Baseball Players] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227144518/http://archive.sportingnews.com/baseball/100|date=February 27, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/history/mlb_history_moreinfo.jsp|title=Al Kaline at The Major League Baseball All-Century Team|publisher=Major League Baseball|work=[[MLB.com]]|date=May 24, 2013|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nCherry Street, which ran behind the left-field stands at [[Tiger Stadium (Detroit)|Tiger Stadium]], was renamed Kaline Drive in his honor in 1970.<ref name=\"The Baseball Biography Project: Al Kaline\"/> On September 27, 1999, when Detroit played its last game at Tiger Stadium against the [[Kansas City Royals]], Kaline was invited to appear in uniform and present the last lineup card to the umpires. He did so along with [[George Brett]], the [[Kansas City Royals]]' great and eventual Hall of Famer.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dow|first=Bill|title=When Tiger Stadium closed, Detroit lost a piece of its soul|date=September 27, 2019|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|url=https://www.freep.com/story/sports/mlb/tigers/2019/09/27/tiger-stadium-close-in-detroit/2427956001/|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nKaline was regarded as a well-rounded player by his contemporaries. [[Baltimore Orioles]] third baseman [[Brooks Robinson]] said of him, \"There have been a lot of great defensive players. The fella who could do everything is Al Kaline. He was just the epitome of what a great outfielder is all about \u2013 great speed, catches the ball and throws the ball well.\"<ref name=hof_bio/> Manager [[Billy Martin]] once said, \"I have always referred to Al Kaline as 'Mister Perfection'. He does it all \u2013 hitting, fielding, running, throwing \u2013 and he does it with that extra touch of brilliancy that marks him as a super ballplayer... Al fits in anywhere, at any position in the lineup and any spot in the batting order.\"<ref>Hawkins, p. 225.</ref>\n\n==Post-playing career==\n[[File:Al Kaline 1995.jpg|thumb|Kaline in 1995]]\nAfter his playing career, Kaline lived in the [[Detroit]] area, and he remained active within the Tigers organization, serving first as a [[color commentator]] on the team's television broadcasts (1975\u20132002) mostly with play by play announcer and former Tiger and fellow Hall of Famer [[George Kell]], and then later as a consultant to the team.<ref name=\"The Baseball Biography Project: Al Kaline\"/> Starting in 2003, Kaline served as a special assistant to Tigers President/CEO/General Manager [[Dave Dombrowski]],<ref name=\"The Baseball Biography Project: Al Kaline\"/> and his duties included coaching/mentoring outfielders during [[spring training]].<ref>Gage, Tom. \"Tigers 'lifer' Al Kaline stays in background but still commands attention.\" ''Detroit News'', February 23, 2011. [http://detnews.com/article/20110223/SPORTS0104/102230318/1129/rss15]{{dead link|date=September 2012}}</ref> Former Tigers teammate Willie Horton also holds this position, and the two threw out the first pitch of the [[2006 World Series]] at [[Comerica Park]].<ref name=\"The Baseball Biography Project: Al Kaline\"/> Kaline continued in his assistant role until his death in 2020. His 67 years with one team was one of the longest tenures in MLB history.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bradburn|first=Michael|title=Al Kaline, 'Mr. Tiger,' dies at 85|date=April 6, 2020|work=The Score|url=https://www.thescore.com/mlb/news/1969086/al-kaline-mr-tiger-dies-at-85|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBecause of his lengthy career and longtime association with the Tigers organization, Kaline's nickname was \"Mr. Tiger.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://detroit.tigers.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20100325&content_id=8922348&vkey=pr_det&fext=.jsp&c_id=det|title=Six: A Salute to Al Kaline|date=March 25, 2010|publisher=Detroit Tigers|work=[[MLB.com]]|accessdate=August 7, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615103616/http://detroit.tigers.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20100325&content_id=8922348&vkey=pr_det&fext=.jsp&c_id=det|archivedate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> Kaline's grandson [[Colin Kaline]] was selected by the Tigers in the 25th round of the [[2007 MLB draft]]. He did not sign, choosing to play baseball at [[Florida Southern College]].<ref>Hawkins, p. 248.</ref> The team drafted him again in the [[2011 MLB draft]], this time in the 26th round. He played in the low minor leagues with the Detroit organization in 2011\u201312.<ref name=America>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseballamerica.com/statistics/players/cards/94678|title=Colin Kaline, 3b, Tigers|publisher=[[Baseball America]]|work=baseballamerica.com|accessdate=February 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKaline married his high school sweetheart, Madge Louise Hamilton, in 1954. He had two sons, Mark Albert Kaline (b. August 21, 1957) and Michael Keith Kaline (b. 1962).<ref name=\"SABR\">{{cite web|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/a141b60c|title=Al Kaline|last=Waddell|first=Nick|publisher=[[SABR]]|work=SABR.org|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Michael played college baseball at [[Miami University]] and is the father of Colin Kaline, who had a short Minor League career and was a college coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/page2/story/_/id/6846924/al-kaline-throws-ceremonial-first-pitch-grandson-colin|title=Al Kaline throws ceremonial first pitch to grandson Colin|publisher=[[ESPN]]|work=ESPN.com |date=August 9, 2011|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=kaline001col|title=Colin Kaline Minor Leagues Statistics & History|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nKaline died in his home in [[Bloomfield Hills, Michigan]], on April 6, 2020; the cause of death was not reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/sports/mlb/tigers/2020/04/06/al-kaline-dies-detroit-tigers/505371001|title=Tigers legend Al Kaline dies at age 85|date=April 6, 2020|last=Lowe|first=John|publisher=[[Detroit Free Press]]|work=freep.com|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball|Biography}}\n* [[List of members of the Baseball Hall of Fame]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball retired numbers]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career hits leaders]]\n* [[List of Gold Glove Award winners at outfield]]\n* [[List of baseball players who went directly to Major League Baseball]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career doubles leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs scored leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs batted in leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career home run leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career total bases leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball players who spent their entire career with one franchise]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Al Kaline}}\n{{bbhof|kaline-al}}\n{{baseballstats |mlb=116822 |espn=23542 |br=k/kalinal01 |fangraphs=1006678 |brm=kaline001alb |retro=K/Pkalia101}}\n*[https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/a141b60c Al Kaline] at SABR (Baseball BioProject)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140709174612/http://www.baseballlibrary.com/ballplayers/player.php?name=Al_Kaline_1934 Al Kaline] at Baseball Library\n*{{findagrave|208777395}}\n*[http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-3407900286.html Al Kaline at Encyclopedia.com]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060507081143/http://www.thebaseballpage.com/players/kalinal01.php Al Kaline at The Baseball Page]\n*[https://archive.today/20130703185506/http://apps.detnews.com/apps/history/index.php?id=145 ''Al Kaline&nbsp;\u2013 the Detroit Tigers' 'Mr. Perfection''' at the ''Detroit News'']\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=gzMDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA52&dq=baseball+digest+al+kaline#v=onepage&q=baseball%20digest%20al%20kaline&f=false \"Why The Red Sox Passed Up Al Kaline\", ''Baseball Digest'', February 1971]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=5zIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA25&dq=baseball+digest+al+kaline#v=onepage&q=baseball%20digest%20al%20kaline&f=false \"Al Kaline: I Want 3000 Hits\", ''Baseball Digest'', July 1972]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=XC4DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA67&dq=baseball+digest+al+kaline#v=onepage&q=baseball%20digest%20al%20kaline&f=false Al Kaline profile, ''Baseball Digest'', February 1991]\n\n{{1968 Detroit Tigers}}\n{{AL batting title}}\n{{Roberto Clemente Award}}\n{{Lou Gehrig Memorial Award}}\n{{Hutch Award}}\n{{AL OF Gold Glove Award}}\n{{3000 hit club}}\n{{Detroit Tigers retired numbers}}\n{{1980 Baseball HOF}}\n{{Baseball Hall of Fame members}}\n{{Detroit Tigers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kaline, Al}}\n[[Category:National Baseball Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Detroit Tigers broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Detroit Tigers players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball right fielders]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball designated hitters]]\n[[Category:Gold Glove Award winners]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Maryland]]\n[[Category:American League batting champions]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball players with retired numbers]]\n[[Category:American sportsmen]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{About|the baseball player|other uses|Alkali (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Al Kaline\n|image=Al Kaline 1957.jpg\n|caption=Kaline in 1957\n|position=[[Right fielder]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1934|12|19}}\n|death_date={{Death date and age|2020|04|06|1934|12|19}}\n|birth_place=[[Baltimore, Maryland]]\n|death_place=[[Bloomfield Hills, Michigan]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=June 25\n|debutyear=1953\n|debutteam=Detroit Tigers\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=October 2\n|finalyear=1974\n|finalteam=Detroit Tigers\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.297\n|stat2label=[[Hit (baseball)|Hits]]\n|stat2value=3,007\n|stat3label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat3value=399\n|stat4label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat4value=1,583\n|teams=\n* [[Detroit Tigers]] ({{mlby|1953}}\u2013{{mlby|1974}})\n|highlights=\n* 18\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1955 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1955]]\u2013[[1961 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (second game)|1961\u00b2]], [[1962 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (second game)|1962\u00b2]]\u2013[[1967 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1967]], [[1971 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1971]], [[1974 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1974]])\n* [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|1968}})\n* 10\u00d7 [[Gold Glove Award]] (1957\u20131959, 1961\u20131967)\n* [[Roberto Clemente Award]] (1973)\n* [[List of Major League Baseball Batting Champions|AL batting champion]] (1955)\n* [[Detroit Tigers#Retired numbers|Detroit Tigers No. 6]] retired\n|hoflink = National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum\n|hoftype = National\n|hofdate=[[1980 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|1980]]\n|hofvote=88.3% (first ballot)\n}}\n\n'''Albert William Kaline''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|e\u026a|l|a\u026a|n}} {{Respell|KAY|line}}; December 19, 1934 \u2013 April 6, 2020), nicknamed \"'''Mr. Tiger'''\", was an American professional [[baseball]] [[right fielder]] who played 22 seasons in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) for the [[Detroit Tigers]].<ref name=br_stats/> For most of his career, Kaline played in the [[outfield]], mainly as a right fielder where he won ten [[Gold Glove Award]]s and was known for his strong throwing arm.<ref>{{cite web|title=Al Kaline |url=http://www.thebaseballpage.com/players/kalinal01 |publisher=The Baseball Page.com |accessdate=August 7, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110804230316/http://www.thebaseballpage.com/players/kalinal01 |archivedate=August 4, 2011 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He was selected to 18 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Games]], including selections each year between 1955 and 1967. He was elected to the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] in [[1980 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|1980]].<ref name=br_stats>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/k/kalinal01.shtml|title=Al Kaline Stats|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 7, 2011}}</ref><ref name=hof_bio>{{cite web|title=Al Kaline biography|url=http://baseballhall.org/hof/kaline-al|publisher=National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|accessdate=August 7, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717211921/http://baseballhall.org/hof/kaline-al|archivedate=July 17, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNear the end of his career, Kaline also played as [[first baseman]] and, in his last season, was the Tigers' [[designated hitter]]. He retired soon after reaching the [[3,000 hit club|3,000 hit]] milestone. Immediately after retiring from playing, he became the Tigers' TV [[color commentator]], a position he held until 2002. Kaline worked for the Tigers as a front office official until his death in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=Al Kaline \u2013 Special Assistant to the President |url=http://detroit.tigers.mlb.com/det/team/team_frontoffice_bio.jsp?loc=al_kaline |publisher=Detroit Tigers |accessdate=August 7, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615103612/http://detroit.tigers.mlb.com/det/team/team_frontoffice_bio.jsp?loc=al_kaline |archivedate=June 15, 2011 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nKaline was born and raised in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], the son of Naomi (Morgan) and Nicholas Kaline.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=VZYYAAAAIAAJ&q=%22Naomi+Morgan%22+Kaline&dq=%22Naomi+Morgan%22+Kaline&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiP4arD_djoAhVEnuAKHSJ3ARQQ6AEwAHoECAAQAQ]</ref> His family was poor. Several of his relatives played [[Semi-professional sports|semi-professional]] baseball, but no one in the family had graduated from high school. When he was eight years old, Kaline developed [[osteomyelitis]] and had a segment of bone removed from his left foot. The surgery left him with scarring and permanent deformity, but he was an outstanding [[pitcher]] in youth baseball.<ref name=SI/> Kaline had learned to throw a [[fastball]], [[changeup]] and [[curveball]] by the age of nine.<ref name=Tigers>{{cite book|last=Pattison|first=Mark, Raglin, David|title=Detroit Tigers 1984: What a Start! What a Finish!|publisher=[[Society for American Baseball Research]]|isbn=1933599456|page=217|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5dcAAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA217|accessdate=January 9, 2014|chapter=Al Kaline}}</ref>\n\nKaline attended Baltimore's [[Southern High School (Baltimore)|Southern High School]], where he starred in basketball and also played football until he sustained a cheek injury. When he tried out for the baseball team, there was no room on the pitching staff so Kaline moved to the outfield.<ref name=Tigers/> He earned all-state honors in baseball all four years.<ref name=SI>{{cite news|last=Olsen|first=Jack|title=The Torments of Excellence|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1075925/1/index.htm|accessdate=April 20, 2013|newspaper=Sports Illustrated|date=May 11, 1964}}</ref> Kaline said that he was a poor student but that he was well liked by his teachers. He said that his teachers passed him and that they believed he would become a baseball player.<ref>Hawkins, p. 18.</ref>\n\n== MLB career ==\n\n=== Early days ===\n[[Image:A Kaline at bat.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Kaline in 1957]]\nKaline bypassed [[Minor League Baseball]] and joined the Tigers directly from high school as an 18-year-old \"[[Bonus Rule|bonus baby]]\" signee, receiving $35,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|35000|1953}}}} in today's dollars) to sign with the team.<ref>{{cite book|title=Official Profile, Photo and Data Book|year=1957|publisher=Detroit Tigers|page=29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tigers Pay $95,000 Bonus Money For School Hurler and Outfielder|url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0A10F63D5B177B93C1AB178DD85F478585F9#|work=The New York Times|accessdate=October 2, 2008|date=June 23, 1953}}</ref>  The Detroit scout who had tracked him through high school, Ed Katalinas, said \"To me he was the prospect that a scout creates in his mind and then prays that someone will come along to fit the pattern.\"<ref>https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/a141b60c</ref>\n\nHe made his major league debut on June 25, [[1953 Detroit Tigers season|1953]] in [[Philadelphia]] as a late-inning replacement for outfielder [[Jim Delsing]]. Kaline wore number 25 during his rookie campaign, but asked teammate [[Pat Mullin]] for his No. 6 after the 1953 season ended. Kaline wore the number for the rest of his major league playing career.<ref>Hawkins, p. 53.</ref>\n\nIn [[1955 Detroit Tigers season|1955]], at age 20, Kaline ended the season with a .340 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]], becoming the youngest player ever to win the [[American League]] (AL) [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions|batting title]]. No 20-year-old major league player had won a batting title since [[Ty Cobb]] in 1907. During the 1955 season, Kaline became the 13th man in major league history to hit two [[home run]]s in the same inning, became the youngest to hit three home runs in one game, and finished the year with 200&nbsp;[[Hit (baseball)|hits]], 27&nbsp;home runs and 102&nbsp;[[runs batted in]] (RBIs).<ref name=br_stats/><ref>{{cite web|title=Two home runs in one inning |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/history/rare_feats/index.jsp?feature=two_homers_inning |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=August 7, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719161531/http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/history/rare_feats/index.jsp?feature=two_homers_inning |archivedate=July 19, 2011 |url-status=live  }}</ref>  He also finished second to [[Yogi Berra]] in the American League's 1955 [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] voting.<ref>{{cite web|title=Baseball Awards Voting for 1955|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/awards_1955.shtml#ALmvp|website=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=August 7, 2011}}</ref> He was selected to the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game]], the first in a string of consecutive All-Star selections that lasted through 1967.<ref name=br_stats/>\n\nKaline followed in [[1956 Detroit Tigers season|1956]] with a .314 batting average with 27&nbsp;home runs and 128&nbsp;RBIs.<ref name=br_stats/> He led the league in outfield [[assist (baseball)|assists]] with 18 in 1956<ref>{{cite web|title=1956 American League Fielding Leaders|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1956-fielding-leaders.shtml|publisher=Baseballreference.com|accessdate=August 7, 2011}}</ref> and again in [[1958 Detroit Tigers season|1958]] with 23.<ref>{{cite web|title=1958 American League Fielding Leaders|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/1958-fielding-leaders.shtml|website=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=August 7, 2011}}</ref> Kaline was out for several games in 1958 after he was hit by a pitch. He missed several games in 1959 after he was hit by a thrown ball and sustained a fracture in his cheekbone. Kaline had been knocked out from the blow and initial speculation was that he could miss six weeks of the season.<ref>Hawkins, p. 92.</ref>\n\n===Middle career===\nIn [[1961 Detroit Tigers season|1961]], Kaline hit .324 to finish second in the AL batting race (behind teammate [[Norm Cash]]). The Tigers won 101 games, to date the third-highest win total in team history, but still finished eight games behind a [[New York Yankees]] team that was led by the home run heroics of [[Roger Maris]] and [[Mickey Mantle]]. Kaline began the [[1962 Detroit Tigers season|1962 season]] hitting .345 with 13 home runs and 38 RBIs in 35 games. On May 26 of that season, he sustained a broken collarbone while making a game-ending catch on a ball hit by New York's [[Elston Howard]]. He missed 57 games due to the injury and Detroit was unable to seriously compete for a pennant due to his absence. When healthy Kaline was great in 1962, hitting 29 home runs and driving in 94 runs in only 100 games.<ref name=Rathet/>\n\nBy late March 1963, Kaline said that he felt good and he was hitting .373 in 53 spring training at-bats.<ref name=Rathet>{{cite news|last=Rathet|first=Mike|title=Al Kaline is Back in Groove|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GwBPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NEsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6908,3191987|accessdate=September 15, 2013|newspaper=[[Ellensburg Daily Record]]|date=March 28, 1963}}</ref> In the [[1963 Detroit Tigers season|1963]] regular season, Kaline hit .312 with 27 home runs and 101 RBIs, finishing second to Elston Howard in the American League's Most Valuable Player Award voting.<ref name=br_stats/><ref>{{cite web|title=Baseball Awards Voting for 1963|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/awards_1963.shtml#ALmvp|website=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=August 7, 2011}}</ref> Kaline experienced pain in his left foot, the one that had been affected by osteomyelitis as a child, throughout the 1964 season. His batting average dropped to .293 that season. Kaline tried to ignore the pain, but he saw physicians who thought he was suffering from [[gout]] and administered injections.<ref name=Crazy/>\n\nStill in pain the following season, Kaline saw an [[orthopedic surgeon]] who prescribed corrective shoes. \"I feel so much better than I did before, that it's ridiculous\", Kaline said by June 1965.<ref name=Crazy>{{cite news|title=Al Kaline: \"Crazy Toes\"|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=f0pQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BFcDAAAAIBAJ&dq=al%20kaline&pg=6550%2C504864|accessdate=September 15, 2013|newspaper=[[Evening Independent]]|date=June 3, 1965}}</ref> Sportswriter Milton Gross described Kaline's deformed foot, saying, \"The pinky and middle finger don't touch the ground. The fourth toe is stretched. The second and third are shortened. The first and third toes overlap the second and the fourth is beginning to overlap the big toe, which has begun to bend to the left. It is hard to believe, but for all of his career with the Tigers while he has been called the perfect player, Kaline has bordered on being a cripple.\"<ref name=Crazy/>\n\nIn the summer of 1967, the normally calm Kaline broke a bone in his hand when he struck a baseball bat against a bat rack.<ref name=Hand>{{cite news|title=Al Kaline Breaks Hand in Fit of Temper|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=RJ8yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8ukFAAAAIBAJ&pg=459,2456981|accessdate=September 16, 2013|newspaper=[[The Miami News]]|date=June 28, 1967}}</ref>  Kaline missed a month of play. When he returned, the Tigers were in a four-team pennant race, but the team finished a game out of first place.<ref name=Prince/> Kaline missed two months of the [[1968 Detroit Tigers season|1968]] season with a [[Bone fracture|broken arm]], but he returned to the [[Batting order (baseball)|lineup]] when Tiger manager [[Mayo Smith]] benched [[shortstop]] [[Ray Oyler]] and sent center fielder [[Mickey Stanley]] to play shortstop to make room for Kaline in the outfield.<ref name=\"The Baseball Biography Project: Al Kaline\">{{cite web|url=http://bioproj.sabr.org/bioproj.cfm?a=v&v=l&bid=1902&pid=7253|title=The Baseball Biography Project: Al Kaline|last=Waddell|first=Nick|publisher=Society for American Baseball Research|accessdate=May 3, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714071926/http://bioproj.sabr.org/bioproj.cfm?a=v&v=l&bid=1902&pid=7253|archivedate=July 14, 2010}}</ref> [[ESPN]] later called Smith's move one of the ten greatest coaching decisions of the century.<ref>{{cite web|title=Greatest coaching decisions|url=http://espn.go.com/endofcentury/s/other/coaches.html|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=August 7, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717214921/http://espn.go.com/endofcentury/s/other/coaches.html|archivedate=July 17, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>  In the [[1968 World Series]], the [[1968 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis Cardinals]] won three of the first four games of the series and were leading Game 5 by a score of 3\u20132 in the seventh inning, when Kaline hit a [[bases loaded]] [[Single (baseball)|single]] to drive in two [[Run (baseball)|runs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/DET/DET196810070.shtml |title=1968 World Series Game 5 box score|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref> The Tigers won that game, and then won Game 6 in a blowout. Kaline had two hits, two runs scored and three RBI in the Tigers' 10-run third inning of Game 6. Detroit went on to win Game 7 for their first world championship since [[1945 Detroit Tigers season|1945]]. In his only World Series appearance, Kaline hit .379 with two home runs and eight RBIs in seven games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1968_WS.shtml|title=1968 World Series|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref> For their victory, Kaline and his teammates each received bonus checks of $10,000 (at a time when Kaline's salary was \"about $70,000\").<ref name=Waldstein>{{cite news|last=Waldstein|first=David|title=Postseason Paychecks Are All About Sharing|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/05/sports/postseason-paychecks-are-all-about-sharing.html?ref=sports|accessdate=October 5, 2014|issue=56645|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|work=nytimes.com|date=October 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Final seasons===\nIn [[1970 Detroit Tigers season|1970]], Kaline was nearly a victim of a freak accident on the baseball field. In a game at [[Milwaukee]]'s [[County Stadium]] on May 30, against the [[Milwaukee Brewers]], Kaline collided with center fielder [[Jim Northrup (baseball)|Jim Northrup]] as they both pursued a fly ball. Kaline fell to the warning track injured. Alertly, left fielder [[Willie Horton (baseball)|Willie Horton]] rushed over and quickly recognized that Kaline was turning blue. Horton reached in and cleared Kaline's airway, saving his life.<ref name=tlkstre>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QSlPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yQEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5588%2C2193279 |work=Toledo Blade |location=(Ohio) |agency=Associated Press |title=Tigers lose, Kaline set to return |date=June 1, 1970 |page=16}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dow |first1=Bill |title=The Day Willie Horton Saved Al Kaline's Life |date=May 27, 2015 |publisher=Detroit Athletic Co. blog |url=http://blog.detroitathletic.com/2015/05/27/the-day-willie-horton-saved-al-kalines-life/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613063546/http://blog.detroitathletic.com/2015/05/27/the-day-willie-horton-saved-al-kalines-life/ |archivedate=June 13, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAfter hitting .294 in [[1971 Detroit Tigers season|1971]], Kaline became the first Tiger to sign a $100,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|100000|1971}}}} in today's dollars) contract. He had turned down a pay raise from $95,000 to $100,000 the previous year, saying he did not feel like he deserved it after hitting .278 with 16 home runs in 1970.<ref name=erghthd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=JdszAAAAIBAJ&sjid=GuEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6426%2C5657586 |work=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon)|agency=Associated Press |title=Detroit star accepts $100,000 contract |date=December 21, 1971 |page=3D}}</ref><ref name=Contract>{{cite news|title=Al Kaline lands $100,000 contract|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rwswAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4gEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5411,3408646 |newspaper=Toledo Blade |location=(Ohio) |agency=Associated Press |date=December 20, 1971}}</ref> Detroit contended all season for the [[1972 Detroit Tigers season|1972]] pennant, trailing the [[1972 Boston Red Sox season|Red Sox]] by a half-game before a series against them to end the regular season.<ref name=Sumter>{{cite news|title=Boston, Detroit start series for pennant|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2mkiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=T6oFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2282,60317 |newspaper=Sumter Daily Item|location=(South Carolina)|agency=Associated Press|date=October 2, 1972|page=11}}</ref> Kaline batted eight times in two games, registering five hits and three runs scored.<ref name=Retro1972>{{cite web|title=The 1972 DET A Regular Season Batting Log for Al Kaline|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1972/Ikalia1010201972.htm|publisher=[[Retrosheet]]|accessdate=October 31, 2013}}</ref> Detroit won those first two games and clinched the AL East pennant.<ref name=DET1972>{{cite web|title=The 1972 Detroit Tigers Regular Season Game Log|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1972/VDET01972.htm|publisher=[[Retrosheet]]|accessdate=October 31, 2013}}</ref><ref name=Out>{{cite news|title=4 Managers Out, 2 Back|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oLkoAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZikEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4584,4968968|accessdate=October 31, 2013|newspaper=Milwaukee Journal|date=October 6, 1972}}</ref> They lost the [[1972 American League Championship Series]] to the [[1972 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]] that year after [[Reggie Jackson]] stole home in the final game of the series.<ref name=Snyder>{{cite news|last=Snyder|first=Matt|title=VIDEO: When Reggie Jackson stole home in A's-Tigers ALCS game|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/eye-on-baseball/24006546/video-when-reggie-jackson-stole-home-in-astigers-alcs-game|accessdate=October 31, 2013|newspaper=[[CBS Sports]]|date=October 4, 2013}}</ref> In March [[1973 Detroit Lions season|1973]], Kaline won the [[Roberto Clemente Award]] in recognition of the honor he brought to baseball on and off the field.<ref name=Honored>{{cite news|title=Al Kaline honored|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jfdUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xjwNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6502,4645602 |newspaper=[[Leader-Post]]|location=(Regina, Saskatchewan)|agency=Associated Press |date=March 21, 1973 |page=30}}</ref>\n\nOn September 24, [[1974 Detroit Tigers season|1974]], Kaline became the 12th player in MLB history to reach the [[3,000 hit club|3,000 hit milestone]], when he hit a [[Double (baseball)|double]] off the Orioles' [[Dave McNally]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exhibits.baseballhalloffame.org/3000_hit_club/kaline_al.htm|title=3,000 hit club at the Baseball Hall of Fame|publisher=Exhibits.baseballhalloffame.org|date=September 24, 1974|accessdate=December 26, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150725002953/http://exhibits.baseballhalloffame.org/3000_hit_club/kaline_al.htm|archivedate=July 25, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/boxscore/09241974.shtml|title=September 24, 1974 Tigers-Orioles box score at Baseball Almanac|publisher=[[Baseball Almanac]]|work=baseball-almanac.com|date=|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BAL/BAL197409240.shtml|title=September 24, 1974 Tigers-Orioles box score|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref> After reaching the milestone, Kaline announced that he would retire.<ref name=Prince>{{cite news|title=Al Kaline: Prince of Detroit Reaches His Promised Land|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DkBSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=T3kDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7095,4035079|accessdate=September 15, 2013|newspaper=[[St. Petersburg Times]]|date=September 25, 1974}}</ref> \"I'm glad it's over. I really am. I don't think I'll miss it. I may miss spring training\", Kaline said after his last game on October 3.<ref name=Ottawa>{{cite news|title=Al Kaline finishes great career in dugout|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=La4yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=n-wFAAAAIBAJ&pg=925,1037408|accessdate=September 16, 2013|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|date=October 3, 1974}}</ref>\n\nKaline finished his career with 3,007&nbsp;hits (25th on the all-time list), 498 doubles, 75 triples, 399 home runs (a Tigers record and 43rd on the all-time list), 1,622 runs scored, 1,277 bases on balls, and 1,582 RBIs.<ref name=br_stats/> He batted over .300 nine times in his career to finish with a lifetime batting average of .297 and hit 25-or-more home runs seven times in his career.<ref name=br_stats/> Kaline also holds Tiger career records for games played (2,834), walks (1,277), and sacrifice flies (104).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/DET/leaders_bat.shtml |title=Detroit Tigers Top 10 Career Batting Leaders|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|date=|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> He had more walks than strikeouts (1,020). He had his highest season strikeout total in his final season, with 75. Prior to that, Kaline never struck out more than 66 times in a season. Defensively, he finished his career with an overall .987 [[fielding percentage]].<ref name=\"br_stats\"/>\n\n==Honors==\n{{MLBBioRet\n|Image  = Kaline_DET.png\n|Name   = Al Kaline\n|Number = 6\n|Team   = Detroit Tigers\n|Year   = 1980\n}}\nKaline was elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame in [[1980 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|1980]], becoming the tenth player in history to be inducted in his first year of eligibility.<ref name=hof_bio/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://apps.detnews.com/apps/history/index.php?id=145|title=Al Kaline \u2013 the Detroit Tigers' 'Mr. Perfection'|date=|accessdate=December 26, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130703185506/http://apps.detnews.com/apps/history/index.php?id=145|archivedate=July 3, 2013}}</ref> He was named on 340 of the 385 ballots (88.3%) cast by sportswriters. Kaline and [[Duke Snider]] were the only candidates elected by the sportswriters in 1980. Kaline later said, \"I really never thought I would choose an individual thing that happened just to me over a team thing like the World Series. But I would have to say this is the biggest thing that has ever happened to me.\"<ref>Hawkins, pp. 239-240.</ref>\n\nKaline was honored by the Tigers as the first of their players to have his uniform number (6) [[retired number|retired]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/det/history/retired_numbers.jsp|title=Detroit Tigers retired numbers at mlb.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|work=[[MLB.com]]|date= |accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref> Versatile and well-rounded, he won ten [[Gold Glove Award]]s (1957\u201359 and 1961\u201367) for excellence in the field and appeared in the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] game 15 times (1955\u201367, 1971, 1974).<ref name=br_stats/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/gold_glove_nl.shtml#1957|title=Gold Glove Award winners|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|date=|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref> In 1998, Kaline ranked Number 76 on ''[[The Sporting News]]'' list of the 100 Greatest Baseball Players,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-almanac.com/legendary/lisn100.shtml|title=Sporting News 100 Greatest (1998)|date=1998|publisher=[[Baseball Almanac]]|work=baseball-almanac.com|accessdate=October 10, 2011}}</ref> and was nominated as a finalist for the [[Major League Baseball All-Century Team]].<ref>[http://archive.sportingnews.com/baseball/100 Al Kaline at The Sporting News 100 Greatest Baseball Players] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227144518/http://archive.sportingnews.com/baseball/100|date=February 27, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/history/mlb_history_moreinfo.jsp|title=Al Kaline at The Major League Baseball All-Century Team|publisher=Major League Baseball|work=[[MLB.com]]|date=May 24, 2013|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nCherry Street, which ran behind the left-field stands at [[Tiger Stadium (Detroit)|Tiger Stadium]], was renamed Kaline Drive in his honor in 1970.<ref name=\"The Baseball Biography Project: Al Kaline\"/> On September 27, 1999, when Detroit played its last game at Tiger Stadium against the [[Kansas City Royals]], Kaline was invited to appear in uniform and present the last lineup card to the umpires. He did so along with [[George Brett]], the [[Kansas City Royals]]' great and eventual Hall of Famer.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dow|first=Bill|title=When Tiger Stadium closed, Detroit lost a piece of its soul|date=September 27, 2019|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|url=https://www.freep.com/story/sports/mlb/tigers/2019/09/27/tiger-stadium-close-in-detroit/2427956001/|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nKaline was regarded as a well-rounded player by his contemporaries. [[Baltimore Orioles]] third baseman [[Brooks Robinson]] said of him, \"There have been a lot of great defensive players. The fella who could do everything is Al Kaline. He was just the epitome of what a great outfielder is all about \u2013 great speed, catches the ball and throws the ball well.\"<ref name=hof_bio/> Manager [[Billy Martin]] once said, \"I have always referred to Al Kaline as 'Mister Perfection'. He does it all \u2013 hitting, fielding, running, throwing \u2013 and he does it with that extra touch of brilliancy that marks him as a super ballplayer... Al fits in anywhere, at any position in the lineup and any spot in the batting order.\"<ref>Hawkins, p. 225.</ref>\n\n==Post-playing career==\n[[File:Al Kaline 1995.jpg|thumb|Kaline in 1995]]\nAfter his playing career, Kaline lived in the [[Detroit]] area, and he remained active within the Tigers organization, serving first as a [[color commentator]] on the team's television broadcasts (1975\u20132002) mostly with play by play announcer and former Tiger and fellow Hall of Famer [[George Kell]], and then later as a consultant to the team.<ref name=\"The Baseball Biography Project: Al Kaline\"/> Starting in 2003, Kaline served as a special assistant to Tigers President/CEO/General Manager [[Dave Dombrowski]],<ref name=\"The Baseball Biography Project: Al Kaline\"/> and his duties included coaching/mentoring outfielders during [[spring training]].<ref>Gage, Tom. \"Tigers 'lifer' Al Kaline stays in background but still commands attention.\" ''Detroit News'', February 23, 2011. [http://detnews.com/article/20110223/SPORTS0104/102230318/1129/rss15]{{dead link|date=September 2012}}</ref> Former Tigers teammate Willie Horton also holds this position, and the two threw out the first pitch of the [[2006 World Series]] at [[Comerica Park]].<ref name=\"The Baseball Biography Project: Al Kaline\"/> Kaline continued in his assistant role until his death in 2020. His 67 years with one team was one of the longest tenures in MLB history.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bradburn|first=Michael|title=Al Kaline, 'Mr. Tiger,' dies at 85|date=April 6, 2020|work=The Score|url=https://www.thescore.com/mlb/news/1969086/al-kaline-mr-tiger-dies-at-85|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBecause of his lengthy career and longtime association with the Tigers organization, Kaline's nickname was \"Mr. Tiger.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://detroit.tigers.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20100325&content_id=8922348&vkey=pr_det&fext=.jsp&c_id=det|title=Six: A Salute to Al Kaline|date=March 25, 2010|publisher=Detroit Tigers|work=[[MLB.com]]|accessdate=August 7, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615103616/http://detroit.tigers.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20100325&content_id=8922348&vkey=pr_det&fext=.jsp&c_id=det|archivedate=June 15, 2011}}</ref> Kaline's grandson [[Colin Kaline]] was selected by the Tigers in the 25th round of the [[2007 MLB draft]]. He did not sign, choosing to play baseball at [[Florida Southern College]].<ref>Hawkins, p. 248.</ref> The team drafted him again in the [[2011 MLB draft]], this time in the 26th round. He played in the low minor leagues with the Detroit organization in 2011\u201312.<ref name=America>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseballamerica.com/statistics/players/cards/94678|title=Colin Kaline, 3b, Tigers|publisher=[[Baseball America]]|work=baseballamerica.com|accessdate=February 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKaline married his high school sweetheart, Madge Louise Hamilton, in 1954. He had two sons, Mark Albert Kaline (b. August 21, 1957) and Michael Keith Kaline (b. 1962).<ref name=\"SABR\">{{cite web|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/a141b60c|title=Al Kaline|last=Waddell|first=Nick|publisher=[[SABR]]|work=SABR.org|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Michael played college baseball at [[Miami University]] and is the father of Colin Kaline, who had a short Minor League career and was a college coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/page2/story/_/id/6846924/al-kaline-throws-ceremonial-first-pitch-grandson-colin|title=Al Kaline throws ceremonial first pitch to grandson Colin|publisher=[[ESPN]]|work=ESPN.com |date=August 9, 2011|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=kaline001col|title=Colin Kaline Minor Leagues Statistics & History|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nKaline died in his home in [[Bloomfield Hills, Michigan]], on April 6, 2020; the cause of death was not reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/sports/mlb/tigers/2020/04/06/al-kaline-dies-detroit-tigers/505371001|title=Tigers legend Al Kaline dies at age 85|date=April 6, 2020|last=Lowe|first=John|publisher=[[Detroit Free Press]]|work=freep.com|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball|Biography}}\n* [[List of members of the Baseball Hall of Fame]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball retired numbers]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career hits leaders]]\n* [[List of Gold Glove Award winners at outfield]]\n* [[List of baseball players who went directly to Major League Baseball]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career doubles leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs scored leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs batted in leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career home run leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career total bases leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball players who spent their entire career with one franchise]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Al Kaline}}\n{{bbhof|kaline-al}}\n{{baseballstats |mlb=116822 |espn=23542 |br=k/kalinal01 |fangraphs=1006678 |brm=kaline001alb |retro=K/Pkalia101}}\n*[https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/a141b60c Al Kaline] at SABR (Baseball BioProject)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140709174612/http://www.baseballlibrary.com/ballplayers/player.php?name=Al_Kaline_1934 Al Kaline] at Baseball Library\n*{{findagrave|208777395}}\n*[http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-3407900286.html Al Kaline at Encyclopedia.com]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060507081143/http://www.thebaseballpage.com/players/kalinal01.php Al Kaline at The Baseball Page]\n*[https://archive.today/20130703185506/http://apps.detnews.com/apps/history/index.php?id=145 ''Al Kaline&nbsp;\u2013 the Detroit Tigers' 'Mr. Perfection''' at the ''Detroit News'']\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=gzMDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA52&dq=baseball+digest+al+kaline#v=onepage&q=baseball%20digest%20al%20kaline&f=false \"Why The Red Sox Passed Up Al Kaline\", ''Baseball Digest'', February 1971]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=5zIDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA25&dq=baseball+digest+al+kaline#v=onepage&q=baseball%20digest%20al%20kaline&f=false \"Al Kaline: I Want 3000 Hits\", ''Baseball Digest'', July 1972]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=XC4DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA67&dq=baseball+digest+al+kaline#v=onepage&q=baseball%20digest%20al%20kaline&f=false Al Kaline profile, ''Baseball Digest'', February 1991]\n\n{{1968 Detroit Tigers}}\n{{AL batting title}}\n{{Roberto Clemente Award}}\n{{Lou Gehrig Memorial Award}}\n{{Hutch Award}}\n{{AL OF Gold Glove Award}}\n{{3000 hit club}}\n{{Detroit Tigers retired numbers}}\n{{1980 Baseball HOF}}\n{{Baseball Hall of Fame members}}\n{{Detroit Tigers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kaline, Al}}\n[[Category:National Baseball Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Detroit Tigers broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Detroit Tigers players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball right fielders]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball designated hitters]]\n[[Category:Gold Glove Award winners]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Maryland]]\n[[Category:American League batting champions]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball players with retired numbers]]\n[[Category:American sportsmen]]\n", "name_user": "Howenstein115", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFinal seasons", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al_Kaline"}
{"title_page": "Anne McClain", "text_new": "{{short description|US Army officer and astronaut}}\n{{Infobox astronaut\n| birth_name          = Anne Charlotte McClain\n| image         = Anne C. McClain portrait.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = \n| type          = [[NASA]] Astronaut\n| nationality   = American\n| status        = Active\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1979|6|7}}\n| birth_place   = {{nowrap|[[Spokane, Washington|Spokane]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], U.S.}}\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| occupation    = Test pilot\n| current_occupation = \n| previous_occupation = \n| alma_mater    = [[United States Military Academy|U.S. Military Academy]]<br />[[University of Bath]]<br />[[University of Bristol]]\n| rank          = [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant colonel]], [[United States Army]]\n| space_time    = 203 days 15 hours 16 minutes<ref name=cbs-20190625 />\n| selection    = [[NASA Astronaut Group 21|2013 NASA Group]]\n| evas          = 2\n| eva_time      = 13h 09m\n| missions      = [[Soyuz MS-11]] ([[Expedition 58]]/[[Expedition 59|59]])\n| insignia      = [[Image:Soyuz-MS-11-Mission-Patch.png|50px]] [[Image:ISS Expedition 58 Patch.svg|45px]] [[Image:ISS Expedition 59 Patch.svg|45px]]\n| retirement    = \n| awards        = [[Bronze Star Medal]]\n}}\n'''Anne Charlotte McClain''' (born June 7, 1979) is a [[lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]] in the [[U.S. Army]], [[engineer]] and a [[NASA]] astronaut.<ref name=\"astrobio2018\">{{Include-NASA}}\n{{cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/biographies/anne-c-mcclain/biography|title=Anne C. McClain (Col, U.S. Army) NASA Astronaut|last=Whiting|first=Melanie|date= October 3, 2018|website=nasa.gov|publisher=[[NASA]]|access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref> Her [[call sign]], \"Annimal\", dates back to her bruising rugby days;<!-- Not a typo --><ref name=\"houstonia2016\">{{cite web|url=https://www.houstoniamag.com/articles/2016/5/31/nasa-women-astronauts-mars-june-2016|title=The New Women of NASA|publisher=Houstonia|accessdate=March 29, 2019|last=Devadanam|first=Steven}}</ref> she also uses the call sign in her [[Twitter]] handle, AstroAnnimal. She was the Flight Engineer for [[Expedition 58]]/[[Expedition 59|59]] to the [[International Space Station]]. After being [[outing|outed]] as an [[LGBT]] woman in August 2019, McClain became the second openly LGBT astronaut.{{efn|[[Sally Ride]] is the first known LGBT astronaut, but was not outed until after her death.}}\n\n==Education==\nBorn and raised in [[Spokane, Washington]],<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" /> McClain wanted to become an astronaut at a young age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soldiers.dodlive.mil/2013/08/living-the-dream-soldiers-selected-as-nasa-astronaut-candidates/|title=Living the dream: Soldiers selected as NASA astronaut candidates - Soldiers Magazine|publisher=DODLive|accessdate=December 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823115335/http://soldiers.dodlive.mil/2013/08/living-the-dream-soldiers-selected-as-nasa-astronaut-candidates/|archive-date=August 23, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>  In 1997, McClain graduated from [[Gonzaga Preparatory School]] in Spokane.<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" /> She did a brief stint at Spokane Community College where she played Softball and enrolled in R.O.T.C. at Gonzaga University, waiting on an appointment to the [[United States Military Academy]], West Point, where she earned a bachelor's degree in mechanical engineering and was commissioned an Army officer in 2002.<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" /> She then attended the [[University of Bath]], where she earned a master's degree in aerospace engineering in 2004, and the [[University of Bristol]], where she earned a master's degree in international relations in 2005.<ref name=\"badass2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autostraddle.com/badass-lady-astronaut-candidates-meet-nasas-class-of-2013-193649/|title=Badass Lady Astronaut Candidates: Meet NASA's Class of 2013|date=September 3, 2013|publisher=AutoStraddle.com|accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref> Both master's degrees were completed through a [[Marshall Scholarship]].<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" /> Her work on unsteady aerodynamics and flow visualization of free-to-roll non-slender delta wings was later published through the [[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]].<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" />\n\nMcClain traveled to Africa for eight weeks with [[Operation Crossroads Africa]], working on a construction project in Uganda.<ref>[http://patriotleague.org/news/2010/10/5/Patriot_League_20th_Anniversary_Profiles_Anne_McClain Patriot League - Patriot League 20th anniversary profiles: Anne McClain]</ref>\n\n==Competitive sports==\nMcClain is an avid [[rugby union|rugby]] player who has played in [[Women's Premiership]], the top level of the sport in [[England]], and for the [[United States women's national rugby union team]], known as the Women's Eagles.<ref name=\"badass2013\" /> While her U.S. Army commitments thwarted her international career in rugby and prevented her participation in the [[2006 Women's Rugby World Cup]], she participated at that level for a decade interrupted only by her deployment to Iraq,<ref name=\"badass2013\" /> and credits the sport for her success in becoming an astronaut.<ref name=\"rugby2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usarugby.org/2018/06/from-eagle-to-astronaut/|title=From Eagle to Astronaut|date=June 15, 2018|last=Brooks|first=Ashley|website=usarugby.org|publisher=USA Rugby|access-date=August 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an interview published in the [[Johnson Space Center|NASA Johnson]] YouTube channel, McClain said that the rugby training was helpful when training with a [[space suit]] in a [[neutral buoyancy pool]].<ref>{{Citation|last=NASA Johnson|title=Astronaut Moments:  Anne McClain|date=2018-11-30|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4LFM3VFSpsQ|access-date=2018-12-01}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n[[File:Expedition 56 backup crew member Anne McClain of NASA.jpg|right|thumb|McClain in [[Army Service Uniform]] in 2018]]\nFollowing her studies, McClain qualified as a [[Bell OH-58 Kiowa|Bell OH-58 Kiowa Warrior]] helicopter pilot. She was deployed to the 2nd Battalion, [[6th Cavalry Regiment]] at [[Wheeler Army Airfield]], [[Hawaii]]. McClain rose through the ranks, starting as an Air Traffic Control Platoon Leader, Aviation Intermediate Maintenance Platoon Leader, to Detachment Commander.<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" />\n\nMcClain was deployed to the Persian Gulf and flew 800 hours and 216 combat missions during the 15 months deployment as part of [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]].<ref name=\"badass2013\" /><ref name=\"astrobio2018\" />\n\nIn 2009, McClain participated in Aviation Captain's Career Course and was then assigned to 1st Battalion, 14th Aviation Regiment at [[Fort Rucker]] as the battalion operations officer and OH-58D instructor. In May 2010, she was appointed Commander of C Troop, 1st Battalion, 14th Aviation Regiment, responsible for the Army's initial entry training, instructor pilot training, and maintenance test pilot training in the OH-58D Kiowa Warrior. She completed Command and General Staff College and the C-12 fixed wing multiengine qualification courses in 2011 and 2012.<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" />\n\nShe also served as a command squadron intelligence officer.<ref name=\"badass2013\" /> McClain graduated from the [[United States Naval Test Pilot School|Naval Test Pilot School]] in June 2013.<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" /> In total, McClain has logged over 2,000 hours on various aircraft type including the Kiowa Warrior, the [[Beechcraft C-12 Huron]], the [[Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk]], and the [[Eurocopter UH-72 Lakota]].<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" />\n\n==NASA career==\n[[File:ISS-58 Anne McClain between the Harmony and the Destiny module.jpg|right|thumb|McClain inside the vestibule between the [[Harmony (ISS module)|Harmony]] and [[Destiny (ISS module)|Destiny]] modules, wearing a sensor on her forehead collecting data on how the [[circadian rhythm]] is affected by long spaceflight]]\n\nIn June 2013, the same month as her graduation as a test pilot, McClain was selected by [[NASA]] as part of [[NASA Astronaut Group 21|Astronaut Group 21]], becoming the youngest astronaut on the NASA roster.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222064049/http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/mcclain-ac.pdf|title=Anne C. McClain|website=nasa.gov|publisher=[[NASA]]|access-date=August 16, 2018}}</ref> She completed training in July 2015, making her available for future missions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/nasa-s-newest-astronauts-complete-training|title=NASA's Newest Astronauts Complete Training|website=nasa.gov|publisher=[[NASA]]|access-date=August 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Expedition 58 / 59 ===\nMcClain successfully launched aboard [[Soyuz MS-11]] to the [[International Space Station]] at 06.32 ET (11.32 GMT) on December 3, 2018, from the cosmodrome in Baikonur, Kazakhstan. She was the flight engineer of [[Expedition 58]]/[[Expedition 59|59]], where she replaced fellow NASA astronaut [[Serena Au\u00f1\u00f3n-Chancellor]], who instead launched earlier with [[Expedition 56]]/[[Expedition 57|57]] due to personnel reassignments. McClain launched with Canadian astronaut [[David Saint-Jacques]] and Russian cosmonaut [[Oleg Kononenko]].<ref name=\"launch\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/station/expeditions/future.html|title= Future Expeditions|website=nasa.gov|publisher=[[NASA]]|access-date=August 16, 2018|quote=\"Expedition 58-59; Launch: Dec. 20, 2018; Crew: [[Oleg Kononenko]], [[David Saint-Jacques]], Anne McClain\"}}</ref> The launch was originally scheduled for December 20, 2018, but was rescheduled to the earlier date after the failure of [[Soyuz MS-10]] with [[Expedition 57]]/58 on October 11, 2018.\n\nOn March 22, 2019, McClain and [[Nick Hague]] performed their first [[Spacewalk]] to install the adapter plates while [[Dextre]] swaps the batteries between spacewalks. The [[Extravehicular activity|extravehicular activity (EVA)]] lasted 6 hours and 39 minutes. They also removed debris from the [[Unity (ISS module)|Unity Module]] in preparation for the arrival of [[Cygnus NG-11]] in April, stowing tools for the repair of the flex hose rotary coupler, and securing tiebacks on the solar array blanket boxes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/2019/03/22/spacewalkers-complete-battery-swaps-for-station-power-upgrades/|title=Spacewalkers Complete Battery Swaps for Station Power Upgrades}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ISS-59 EVA-1 (p) Anne McClain takes a space-selfie.jpg|thumb|McClain takes a selfie during her first spacewalk, Expedition 59 EVA 1, on March 22, 2019.]]\nMcClain was scheduled to perform a second EVA on March 29, with [[Christina Koch]], which would have been the first all-female spacewalk,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/06/us/nasa-first-all-female-spacewalk-trnd/index.html|title=2 astronauts are scheduled for the first all-female spacewalk in history|author=Gianluca Mezzofiore|website=CNN|access-date=2019-03-18}}</ref> but spacesuit sizing issues resulted in this EVA's being reassigned to Hague and Koch.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Berger |first1=Eric |title=It's unfortunate NASA canceled the all-female EVA, but it's the right decision |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2019/03/yes-nasa-has-canceled-an-all-female-spacewalk-no-its-not-a-conspiracy/ |work=Ars Technica |date=March 26, 2019 |language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Spacewalkers Swapping Places; Crew Studies Brain and Muscles \u2013 Space Station |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/2019/03/26/spacewalkers-swapping-places-crew-studies-brain-and-muscles/ |website=blogs.nasa.gov |publisher=NASA}}</ref> McClain conducted a second spacewalk with Saint-Jacques on April 8.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harding |first1=Pete |last2=Bergin |first2=Chris |title=Following ISS battery upgrade, EVA-54 works on power systems |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2019/04/astronauts-begin-spacewalk-replace-stations-batteries/ |work=NASASpaceFlight.com}}</ref>\n\nMcClain, Saint-Jacques and Kononenko returned to Earth on board Soyuz MS-11 on June 24, 2019.<ref name=cbs-20190625>{{cite news |last1=Harwood |first1=William |title=3 station fliers complete \"once-in-a-lifetime ride\" home after 204-day stay in orbit |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/soyuz-3-station-fliers-wrap-up-204-day-stay-in-orbit-landing-complete-kazakhstan-today-2019-06-24/ |work=CBS News |date=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nMcClain is a recipient of the [[Bronze Star Medal]], the [[Air Medal]] with [[\"V\" Device|Valor device]], two additional Air Medals, two [[Army Commendation Medal]]s, two [[Army Achievement Medal]]s, the [[Iraq Campaign Medal]] with two service stars, the [[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]], and three [[Overseas Service Ribbon]]s.<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nMcClain married Summer Worden in 2014<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/23/us/nasa-astronaut-anne-mcclain.html|title=How a Bitter Divorce Battle on Earth Led to Claims of a Crime in Space|last=Baker|first=Mike|date=2019-08-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-08-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/23/politics/nasa-astronaut-bank-account-first-criminal-allegation-space/index.html|title=New York Times: Astronaut accessed estranged spouse's bank account in possible first criminal allegation from space|author=Caroline Kelly|website=CNN|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref> and is step-mother to Worden's son. McClain and Worden have filed for divorce.<ref name=\":1\"/> In August 2017, McClain brought her step-child for the official NASA portrait session,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/nasa-astronaut-mom-son-portrait-2018-3|title=Astronaut Anne McClain brought her 4-year-old son to a NASA photo shoot before flying to space, and the pictures will melt your heart |author=Dave Mosher |publisher=Business Insider |date=March 20, 2019}}</ref> but the photographs were removed from NASA's official portraits after Worden complained.<ref name=\"Bartels\">{{cite news|url=https://www.space.com/nasa-astronaut-anne-mcclain-space-crime-claim.html|title=A NASA Astronaut's Divorce Has Sparked Claims of a Crime in Space: Report|last=Bartels|first=Meghan|date=August 23, 2019|work=Space.com|access-date=August 23, 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn August 23, 2019, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that Worden has filed a complaint against McClain through the Federal Trade Commission accusing her of illegally accessing financial information while residing in the International Space Station.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/nasa-astronaut-accused-hacking-her-estranged-spouse-s-bank-account-n1046061|title=A top NASA astronaut accused of hacking her estranged spouse's bank account from space|last=Acevedo|first=Nicole|date=August 24, 2019|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=August 24, 2019 }}</ref> This accusation outed McClain as a [[LGBT]] woman, making her the second openly LGBT astronaut because of Sally Ride.<ref name=Bartels/> McClain has unequivocally refuted Worden's claims.<ref>Gohd, Chelsea (August 25, 2019). \"[https://www.space.com/astronaut-anne-mcclain-refutes-space-crime-claim.html Astronaut Anne McClain Refutes Space Crime Claim]\". ''space.com''.</ref> \n\nOn April 7, 2020 McClain was cleared of all charges. Her ex-wife, Summer Worden, a 44-year-old former Air Force intelligence officer, faces a two-count indictment by a federal grand jury in Houston, Texas, issued in late February.<ref>[https://www.armytimes.com/news/your-army/2020/04/07/army-astronaut-accused-of-committing-crime-in-space-is-cleared-ex-wife-charged-with-making-false-statements/ Army Times]</ref>\n\nMcClain resides in suburban [[Houston, Texas]].{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Soyuz MS-09 backup crew at the statue of Sergei Korolev.jpg|[[Soyuz MS-09]] backup crew at the statue of [[Sergei Korolev]] in [[Baikonur]], Kazakhstan,  on May 21, 2018\nFile:Expedition 57 crew gathers inside the Zvezda Service Module.jpg|The newly-expanded six-member [[Expedition 57]] crew poses for a portrait inside the International Space Station's [[Zvezda (ISS module)|Zvezda]] service module on December 10, 2018\nFile:Expedition 57 crew gathers inside the Destiny laboratory.jpg|Expedition 57 crew gathers inside the [[Destiny (ISS module)|Destiny]] laboratory on December 18, 2018\nFile:Expedition 59 crew members in their crew quarters.jpg|Four [[Expedition 59]] astronauts pose for a playful portrait inside the [[Harmony (ISS module)|Harmony]] module on May 4, 2019\nFile:Expedition 59 Soyuz MS-11 Landing (NHQ201906250002).jpg|Anne McClain after her first landing near the town of [[Zhezkazgan]] on June 25, 2019\n\n</gallery>\n\n{{-}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|LGBT|Spaceflight|United States}}\n* [[List of female astronauts]]\n* [[List of female explorers and travelers]]\n* [[Women in science]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/biographies/anne-c-mcclain/biography NASA Astronaut Biography]\n* [https://www.nasa.gov/johnson/HWHAP/fly-em-all Houston We Have a Podcast: 'Fly 'em All' an interview with Anne McClain]\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cXNoVoKgtG0 Five things you didn't know about  Astronaut Anne McClain] NASA [[Johnson Space Center]], November 30, 2018\n\n{{NASA Astronaut Group 21|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority Control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McClain, Anne C.}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American astronauts]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bath]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Helicopter pilots]]\n[[Category:People from Spokane, Washington]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Spokane, Washington]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army astronauts]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Test Pilot School alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States Army]]\n[[Category:Marshall Scholars]]\n[[Category:American female aviators]]\n[[Category:American rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Air Medal]]\n[[Category:Crew members of the International Space Station]]\n[[Category:Women astronauts]]\n[[Category:Military personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:American sportswomen]]\n[[Category:Women in the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:American people of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Female rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Military aviators]]\n[[Category:American test pilots]]\n[[Category:American female rugby union players]]\n[[Category:American aviators]]\n[[Category:Female military aviators]]\n[[Category:Lesbian military personnel]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:American LGBT military personnel]]\n[[Category:American engineers]]\n[[Category:United States Army aviators]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|US Army officer and astronaut}}\n{{Infobox astronaut\n| birth_name          = Anne Charlotte McClain\n| image         = Anne C. McClain portrait.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = \n| type          = [[NASA]] Astronaut\n| nationality   = American\n| status        = Active\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1979|6|7}}\n| birth_place   = {{nowrap|[[Spokane, Washington|Spokane]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], U.S.}}\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| occupation    = Test pilot\n| current_occupation = \n| previous_occupation = \n| alma_mater    = [[United States Military Academy|U.S. Military Academy]]<br />[[University of Bath]]<br />[[University of Bristol]]\n| rank          = [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant colonel]], [[United States Army]]\n| space_time    = 203 days 15 hours 16 minutes<ref name=cbs-20190625 />\n| selection    = [[NASA Astronaut Group 21|2013 NASA Group]]\n| evas          = 2\n| eva_time      = 13h 09m\n| missions      = [[Soyuz MS-11]] ([[Expedition 58]]/[[Expedition 59|59]])\n| insignia      = [[Image:Soyuz-MS-11-Mission-Patch.png|50px]] [[Image:ISS Expedition 58 Patch.svg|45px]] [[Image:ISS Expedition 59 Patch.svg|45px]]\n| retirement    = \n| awards        = [[Bronze Star Medal]]\n}}\n'''Anne Charlotte McClain''' (born June 7, 1979) is a [[lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]] in the [[U.S. Army]], [[engineer]] and a [[NASA]] astronaut.<ref name=\"astrobio2018\">{{Include-NASA}}\n{{cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/biographies/anne-c-mcclain/biography|title=Anne C. McClain (Col, U.S. Army) NASA Astronaut|last=Whiting|first=Melanie|date= October 3, 2018|website=nasa.gov|publisher=[[NASA]]|access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref> Her [[call sign]], \"Annimal\", dates back to her bruising rugby days;<!-- Not a typo --><ref name=\"houstonia2016\">{{cite web|url=https://www.houstoniamag.com/articles/2016/5/31/nasa-women-astronauts-mars-june-2016|title=The New Women of NASA|publisher=Houstonia|accessdate=March 29, 2019|last=Devadanam|first=Steven}}</ref> she also uses the call sign in her [[Twitter]] handle, AstroAnnimal. She was the Flight Engineer for [[Expedition 58]]/[[Expedition 59|59]] to the [[International Space Station]]. After being [[outing|outed]] as an [[LGBT]] woman in August 2019, McClain became the second openly LGBT astronaut.{{efn|[[Sally Ride]] is the first known LGBT astronaut, but was not outed until after her death.}}\n\n==Education==\nBorn and raised in [[Spokane, Washington]],<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" /> McClain wanted to become an astronaut at a young age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soldiers.dodlive.mil/2013/08/living-the-dream-soldiers-selected-as-nasa-astronaut-candidates/|title=Living the dream: Soldiers selected as NASA astronaut candidates - Soldiers Magazine|publisher=DODLive|accessdate=December 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180823115335/http://soldiers.dodlive.mil/2013/08/living-the-dream-soldiers-selected-as-nasa-astronaut-candidates/|archive-date=August 23, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>  In 1997, McClain graduated from [[Gonzaga Preparatory School]] in Spokane.<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" /> She did a brief stint at Spokane Community College where she played Softball and enrolled in R.O.T.C. at Gonzaga University, waiting on an appointment to the [[United States Military Academy]], West Point, where she earned a bachelor's degree in mechanical engineering and was commissioned an Army officer in 2002.<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" /> She then attended the [[University of Bath]], where she earned a master's degree in aerospace engineering in 2004, and the [[University of Bristol]], where she earned a master's degree in international relations in 2005.<ref name=\"badass2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autostraddle.com/badass-lady-astronaut-candidates-meet-nasas-class-of-2013-193649/|title=Badass Lady Astronaut Candidates: Meet NASA's Class of 2013|date=September 3, 2013|publisher=AutoStraddle.com|accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref> Both master's degrees were completed through a [[Marshall Scholarship]].<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" /> Her work on unsteady aerodynamics and flow visualization of free-to-roll non-slender delta wings was later published through the [[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]].<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" />\n\nMcClain traveled to Africa for eight weeks with [[Operation Crossroads Africa]], working on a construction project in Uganda.<ref>[http://patriotleague.org/news/2010/10/5/Patriot_League_20th_Anniversary_Profiles_Anne_McClain Patriot League - Patriot League 20th anniversary profiles: Anne McClain]</ref>\n\n==Competitive sports==\nMcClain is an avid [[rugby union|rugby]] player who has played in [[Women's Premiership]], the top level of the sport in [[England]], and for the [[United States women's national rugby union team]], known as the Women's Eagles.<ref name=\"badass2013\" /> While her U.S. Army commitments thwarted her international career in rugby and prevented her participation in the [[2006 Women's Rugby World Cup]], she participated at that level for a decade interrupted only by her deployment to Iraq,<ref name=\"badass2013\" /> and credits the sport for her success in becoming an astronaut.<ref name=\"rugby2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usarugby.org/2018/06/from-eagle-to-astronaut/|title=From Eagle to Astronaut|date=June 15, 2018|last=Brooks|first=Ashley|website=usarugby.org|publisher=USA Rugby|access-date=August 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an interview published in the [[Johnson Space Center|NASA Johnson]] YouTube channel, McClain said that the rugby training was helpful when training with a [[space suit]] in a [[neutral buoyancy pool]].<ref>{{Citation|last=NASA Johnson|title=Astronaut Moments:  Anne McClain|date=2018-11-30|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4LFM3VFSpsQ|access-date=2018-12-01}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n[[File:Expedition 56 backup crew member Anne McClain of NASA.jpg|right|thumb|McClain in [[Army Service Uniform]] in 2018]]\nFollowing her studies, McClain qualified as a [[Bell OH-58 Kiowa|Bell OH-58 Kiowa Warrior]] helicopter pilot. She was deployed to the 2nd Battalion, [[6th Cavalry Regiment]] at [[Wheeler Army Airfield]], [[Hawaii]]. McClain rose through the ranks, starting as an Air Traffic Control Platoon Leader, Aviation Intermediate Maintenance Platoon Leader, to Detachment Commander.<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" />\n\nMcClain was deployed to the Persian Gulf and flew 800 hours and 216 combat missions during the 15 months deployment as part of [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]].<ref name=\"badass2013\" /><ref name=\"astrobio2018\" />\n\nIn 2009, McClain participated in Aviation Captain's Career Course and was then assigned to 1st Battalion, 14th Aviation Regiment at [[Fort Rucker]] as the battalion operations officer and OH-58D instructor. In May 2010, she was appointed Commander of C Troop, 1st Battalion, 14th Aviation Regiment, responsible for the Army's initial entry training, instructor pilot training, and maintenance test pilot training in the OH-58D Kiowa Warrior. She completed Command and General Staff College and the C-12 fixed wing multiengine qualification courses in 2011 and 2012.<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" />\n\nShe also served as a command squadron intelligence officer.<ref name=\"badass2013\" /> McClain graduated from the [[United States Naval Test Pilot School|Naval Test Pilot School]] in June 2013.<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" /> In total, McClain has logged over 2,000 hours on various aircraft type including the Kiowa Warrior, the [[Beechcraft C-12 Huron]], the [[Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk]], and the [[Eurocopter UH-72 Lakota]].<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" />\n\n==NASA career==\n[[File:ISS-58 Anne McClain between the Harmony and the Destiny module.jpg|right|thumb|McClain inside the vestibule between the [[Harmony (ISS module)|Harmony]] and [[Destiny (ISS module)|Destiny]] modules, wearing a sensor on her forehead collecting data on how the [[circadian rhythm]] is affected by long spaceflight]]\n\nIn June 2013, the same month as her graduation as a test pilot, McClain was selected by [[NASA]] as part of [[NASA Astronaut Group 21|Astronaut Group 21]], becoming the youngest astronaut on the NASA roster.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222064049/http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/mcclain-ac.pdf|title=Anne C. McClain|website=nasa.gov|publisher=[[NASA]]|access-date=August 16, 2018}}</ref> She completed training in July 2015, making her available for future missions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/nasa-s-newest-astronauts-complete-training|title=NASA's Newest Astronauts Complete Training|website=nasa.gov|publisher=[[NASA]]|access-date=August 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Expedition 58 / 59 ===\nMcClain successfully launched aboard [[Soyuz MS-11]] to the [[International Space Station]] at 06.32 ET (11.32 GMT) on December 3, 2018, from the cosmodrome in Baikonur, Kazakhstan. She was the flight engineer of [[Expedition 58]]/[[Expedition 59|59]], where she replaced fellow NASA astronaut [[Serena Au\u00f1\u00f3n-Chancellor]], who instead launched earlier with [[Expedition 56]]/[[Expedition 57|57]] due to personnel reassignments. McClain launched with Canadian astronaut [[David Saint-Jacques]] and Russian cosmonaut [[Oleg Kononenko]].<ref name=\"launch\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/station/expeditions/future.html|title= Future Expeditions|website=nasa.gov|publisher=[[NASA]]|access-date=August 16, 2018|quote=\"Expedition 58-59; Launch: Dec. 20, 2018; Crew: [[Oleg Kononenko]], [[David Saint-Jacques]], Anne McClain\"}}</ref> The launch was originally scheduled for December 20, 2018, but was rescheduled to the earlier date after the failure of [[Soyuz MS-10]] with [[Expedition 57]]/58 on October 11, 2018.\n\nOn March 22, 2019, McClain and [[Nick Hague]] performed their first [[Spacewalk]] to install the adapter plates while [[Dextre]] swaps the batteries between spacewalks. The [[Extravehicular activity|extravehicular activity (EVA)]] lasted 6 hours and 39 minutes. They also removed debris from the [[Unity (ISS module)|Unity Module]] in preparation for the arrival of [[Cygnus NG-11]] in April, stowing tools for the repair of the flex hose rotary coupler, and securing tiebacks on the solar array blanket boxes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/2019/03/22/spacewalkers-complete-battery-swaps-for-station-power-upgrades/|title=Spacewalkers Complete Battery Swaps for Station Power Upgrades}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ISS-59 EVA-1 (p) Anne McClain takes a space-selfie.jpg|thumb|McClain takes a selfie during her first spacewalk, Expedition 59 EVA 1, on March 22, 2019.]]\nMcClain was scheduled to perform a second EVA on March 29, with [[Christina Koch]], which would have been the first all-female spacewalk,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/06/us/nasa-first-all-female-spacewalk-trnd/index.html|title=2 astronauts are scheduled for the first all-female spacewalk in history|author=Gianluca Mezzofiore|website=CNN|access-date=2019-03-18}}</ref> but spacesuit sizing issues resulted in this EVA's being reassigned to Hague and Koch.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Berger |first1=Eric |title=It's unfortunate NASA canceled the all-female EVA, but it's the right decision |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2019/03/yes-nasa-has-canceled-an-all-female-spacewalk-no-its-not-a-conspiracy/ |work=Ars Technica |date=March 26, 2019 |language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Spacewalkers Swapping Places; Crew Studies Brain and Muscles \u2013 Space Station |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/spacestation/2019/03/26/spacewalkers-swapping-places-crew-studies-brain-and-muscles/ |website=blogs.nasa.gov |publisher=NASA}}</ref> McClain conducted a second spacewalk with Saint-Jacques on April 8.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harding |first1=Pete |last2=Bergin |first2=Chris |title=Following ISS battery upgrade, EVA-54 works on power systems |url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2019/04/astronauts-begin-spacewalk-replace-stations-batteries/ |work=NASASpaceFlight.com}}</ref>\n\nMcClain, Saint-Jacques and Kononenko returned to Earth on board Soyuz MS-11 on June 24, 2019.<ref name=cbs-20190625>{{cite news |last1=Harwood |first1=William |title=3 station fliers complete \"once-in-a-lifetime ride\" home after 204-day stay in orbit |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/soyuz-3-station-fliers-wrap-up-204-day-stay-in-orbit-landing-complete-kazakhstan-today-2019-06-24/ |work=CBS News |date=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nMcClain is a recipient of the [[Bronze Star Medal]], the [[Air Medal]] with [[\"V\" Device|Valor device]], two additional Air Medals, two [[Army Commendation Medal]]s, two [[Army Achievement Medal]]s, the [[Iraq Campaign Medal]] with two service stars, the [[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]], and three [[Overseas Service Ribbon]]s.<ref name=\"astrobio2018\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nMcClain married Summer Worden in 2014<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/23/us/nasa-astronaut-anne-mcclain.html|title=How a Bitter Divorce Battle on Earth Led to Claims of a Crime in Space|last=Baker|first=Mike|date=2019-08-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-08-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/23/politics/nasa-astronaut-bank-account-first-criminal-allegation-space/index.html|title=New York Times: Astronaut accessed estranged spouse's bank account in possible first criminal allegation from space|author=Caroline Kelly|website=CNN|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref> and is step-mother to Worden's son. McClain and Worden have filed for divorce.<ref name=\":1\"/> In August 2017, McClain brought her step-child for the official NASA portrait session,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/nasa-astronaut-mom-son-portrait-2018-3|title=Astronaut Anne McClain brought her 4-year-old son to a NASA photo shoot before flying to space, and the pictures will melt your heart |author=Dave Mosher |publisher=Business Insider |date=March 20, 2019}}</ref> but the photographs were removed from NASA's official portraits after Worden complained.<ref name=\"Bartels\">{{cite news|url=https://www.space.com/nasa-astronaut-anne-mcclain-space-crime-claim.html|title=A NASA Astronaut's Divorce Has Sparked Claims of a Crime in Space: Report|last=Bartels|first=Meghan|date=August 23, 2019|work=Space.com|access-date=August 23, 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn August 23, 2019, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that Worden has filed a complaint against McClain through the Federal Trade Commission accusing her of illegally accessing financial information while residing in the International Space Station.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/nasa-astronaut-accused-hacking-her-estranged-spouse-s-bank-account-n1046061|title=A top NASA astronaut accused of hacking her estranged spouse's bank account from space|last=Acevedo|first=Nicole|date=August 24, 2019|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=August 24, 2019 }}</ref> This accusation outed McClain as a [[LGBT]] woman, making her the second openly LGBT astronaut because of Sally Ride.<ref name=Bartels/> McClain has unequivocally refuted Worden's claims.<ref>Gohd, Chelsea (August 25, 2019). \"[https://www.space.com/astronaut-anne-mcclain-refutes-space-crime-claim.html Astronaut Anne McClain Refutes Space Crime Claim]\". ''space.com''.</ref> \n\nOn April 7, 2020 McClain was cleared of all charges. Her ex-wife, Summer Worden, a 44-year-old former Air Force intelligence officer, faces a two-count indictment by a federal grand jury in Houston, Texas, issued in late February.\n\n\nhttps://www.armytimes.com/news/your-army/2020/04/07/army-astronaut-accused-of-committing-crime-in-space-is-cleared-ex-wife-charged-with-making-false-statements/\n\nMcClain resides in suburban [[Houston, Texas]].{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Soyuz MS-09 backup crew at the statue of Sergei Korolev.jpg|[[Soyuz MS-09]] backup crew at the statue of [[Sergei Korolev]] in [[Baikonur]], Kazakhstan,  on May 21, 2018\nFile:Expedition 57 crew gathers inside the Zvezda Service Module.jpg|The newly-expanded six-member [[Expedition 57]] crew poses for a portrait inside the International Space Station's [[Zvezda (ISS module)|Zvezda]] service module on December 10, 2018\nFile:Expedition 57 crew gathers inside the Destiny laboratory.jpg|Expedition 57 crew gathers inside the [[Destiny (ISS module)|Destiny]] laboratory on December 18, 2018\nFile:Expedition 59 crew members in their crew quarters.jpg|Four [[Expedition 59]] astronauts pose for a playful portrait inside the [[Harmony (ISS module)|Harmony]] module on May 4, 2019\nFile:Expedition 59 Soyuz MS-11 Landing (NHQ201906250002).jpg|Anne McClain after her first landing near the town of [[Zhezkazgan]] on June 25, 2019\n\n</gallery>\n\n{{-}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|LGBT|Spaceflight|United States}}\n* [[List of female astronauts]]\n* [[List of female explorers and travelers]]\n* [[Women in science]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.nasa.gov/astronauts/biographies/anne-c-mcclain/biography NASA Astronaut Biography]\n* [https://www.nasa.gov/johnson/HWHAP/fly-em-all Houston We Have a Podcast: 'Fly 'em All' an interview with Anne McClain]\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cXNoVoKgtG0 Five things you didn't know about  Astronaut Anne McClain] NASA [[Johnson Space Center]], November 30, 2018\n\n{{NASA Astronaut Group 21|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority Control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McClain, Anne C.}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American astronauts]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bath]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Helicopter pilots]]\n[[Category:People from Spokane, Washington]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Spokane, Washington]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:United States Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army astronauts]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Test Pilot School alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States Army]]\n[[Category:Marshall Scholars]]\n[[Category:American female aviators]]\n[[Category:American rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Air Medal]]\n[[Category:Crew members of the International Space Station]]\n[[Category:Women astronauts]]\n[[Category:Military personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[