ue|2016\u201317]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2017/overview/index.html|title=2016/17: United win it for Manchester|publisher=UEFA|date=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Eredivisie]] Top Assists: [[2014\u201315 Eredivisie#Assists|2014\u201315]], [[2016\u201317 Eredivisie#Assists|2016\u201317]], [[2017\u201318 Eredivisie#Assists|2017\u201318]], [[2018\u201319 Eredivisie#Assists|2018\u201319]] (shared with [[Du\u0161an Tadi\u0107]])\n* Mars d'Or (Moroccan player of the Year): 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffpostmaghreb.com/2016/12/23/convocation-hakim-ziyech_n_13817322.html|title=La non convocation de Hakim Ziyech fait jaser|date=23 December 2016|website=Al HuffPost Maghreb}}</ref>\n*[[Eredivisie]] Team of the Year: [[2016-17 Eredivisie|2016\u201317]], [[2017-18 Eredivisie|2017\u201318]], [[2018-19 Eredivisie|2018\u201319]]\n*[[AFC Ajax]] Player of the Year: [[2017\u201318 AFC Ajax season|2017\u201318]], [[2018\u201319 AFC Ajax season|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sportnieuws.nl/voetbal/ziyech-wint-rinus-michels-trofee-beste-speler-seizoen/|title=Ziyech wint Rinus Michels-trofee voor beste speler van het seizoen |publisher=SportNieuws.nl}}</ref>\n*[[Dutch Footballer of the Year]]: 2017\u201318<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voetbalcentraal.nl/nieuws/273795/Hakim-Ziyech-winnaar-Gouden-Schoen,-Matthijs-de-Ligt-wint-brons|title=Hakim Ziyech winnaar Gouden Schoen, Matthijs de Ligt wint brons|language=Dutch|publisher=Voetbal Centraal|website=voetbalcentraal.nl}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Champions League]] Squad of the Season: [[2018\u201319 UEFA Champions League#Squad of the season|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*[[CAF Team of the Year]]: 2019<ref>{{cite news|title=Mane, Oshoala named African Footballers of 2019 at CAF Awards |url=https://www.cafonline.com/awards/news/mane-oshoala-named-african-footballers-of-2019-at-caf-awards|website=CAFOnline.com |publisher=CAF |date=7 January 2020|accessdate=7 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{portal bar|Association football|Morocco}}\n{{commonscat}}\n*[https://www.vi.nl/spelers/hakim-ziyech/profiel Hakim Ziyech] at ''[[Voetbal International]]'' {{in lang|nl}}\n*{{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225063052/http://www.onsoranje.nl/team-statistieken/teams/speler/25/50a3c219-d68eb070-494153|title=Netherlands U21 stats at OnsOranje|date=25 December 2013}}\n\n{{AFC Ajax squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Morocco squads\n| bg = #BA1219\n| fg = white\n| bordercolor = #006233\n| list1 =\n{{Morocco squad 2018 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Morocco squad 2019 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title       = Awards\n| bg          = Gold\n| bordercolor = #000000\n| list1       =\n{{AFC Ajax Player of the Year}}\n{{Dutch Footballer of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ziyech, Hakim}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch people of Moroccan descent]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Dronten]]\n[[Category:Dutch footballers]]\n[[Category:Moroccan footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:SC Heerenveen players]]\n[[Category:FC Twente players]]\n[[Category:AFC Ajax players]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:Netherlands youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Morocco international footballers]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2019 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: stripped off \u2192 stripped of", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hakim_Ziyech"}
{"title_page": "SAP SE", "text_new": "{{redirect|SAP (company)|other companies|SAP (disambiguation)}}\n{{Short description|European software producer}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{coord|49.2938038|8.639581|display=title}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = SAP SE\n| logo = SAP 2011 logo.svg\n| image = Sap-wdf.jpg\n| image_caption = SAP headquarters in Walldorf, Germany\n| type = ''[[Societas Europaea]]''\n| traded_as = {{FWB|SAP}}<br />{{nyse|SAP}}<br />[[DAX|DAX Component]]\n| caption = \n| foundation = [[Weinheim]], Germany<br />({{start date and age|1972}})\n| founder = [[Dietmar Hopp]]<br />Hans-Werner Hector<br />[[Hasso Plattner]]<br />[[Klaus Tschira]]<br />[[Claus Wellenreuther]]\n| location_city = Dietmar-Hopp-Allee 16, [[Walldorf]], [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n| location_country = Germany\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = * [[Hasso Plattner]] <small>(Chairman) </small>\n* [[Jennifer Morgan]] <small> (co-CEO) </small>\n* [[Christian Klein]] <small> (co-CEO) </small>\n| industry = [[Enterprise software]]\n| products = See [[list of SAP products]]\n| revenue = {{Increase}} [[Euro|\u20ac]]27.553&nbsp;billion <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"financials\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sap.com/docs/download/investors/2019/sap-2019-q4-statement.pdf|title=SAP Q4 2019 Quarterly Statement|publisher=SAP SE|accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n| operating_income = {{Decrease}} \u20ac4.495&nbsp;billion <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"financials\"/>\n| net_income = {{Decrease}} \u20ac3.387&nbsp;billion <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"financials\"/>\n| assets = {{Increase}} \u20ac60.229&nbsp;billion <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"financials\"/>\n| equity = {{Increase}} \u20ac30.839&nbsp;billion <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"financials\"/>\n| num_employees = 100,330 <small>(2019)</small><ref name=\"financials\"/>\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.sap.com/}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''SAP [[Societas Europaea|SE]]''' ({{IPAc-en|\u025b|s|e\u026a|\u02c8|p|i}}; abbreviation of \"'''S'''ystems, '''A'''pplications & '''P'''roducts in Data Processing\") is a European [[Multinational corporation|multinational]] [[software corporation]] that makes [[enterprise software]] to manage business operations and customer relations.<ref name=\"SAP Company History\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sap.com/corporate/en/company/history.html|title=SAP Company History|accessdate=25 January 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.panorama-consulting.com/resource-center/erp-database/sap/|title=SAP Software {{!}} SAP Implementations {{!}} SAP Company Profile|website=Panorama Consulting Solutions|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref> The company is especially known for its [[Enterprise resource planning|ERP software]]. SAP is headquartered in [[Walldorf]], [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], [[Germany]] with regional offices in 180 countries.<ref name=\"SAP Company Information\">{{cite web|url=http://global.sap.com/corporate-en/our-company/index.epx|title=SAP at a Glance: Company Information|accessdate=27 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> The company has over 425,000 customers in over 180 countries<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sap.com/documents/2017/04/4666ecdd-b67c-0010-82c7-eda71af511fa.html|title=SAP Corporate Fact Sheet|website=SAP|language=English|access-date=2019-03-19}}</ref> and is a component of the [[Euro Stoxx 50]] [[stock market index]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boerse-frankfurt.de/en/equities/indices/euro+stoxx+50+EU0009658145/constituents|title=B\u00f6rse Frankfurt (Frankfurt Stock Exchange): Stock market quotes, charts and news|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation===\nWhen [[Xerox]] exited the computer hardware manufacturing industry in 1971,<ref>Holmes, Edith. \"IBM Opposes Retelling of Whole Xerox Story in Court\", ''Computerworld'', p. 42, 26 January 1976.</ref> it asked [[IBM]] to migrate its business systems to [[IBM]] technology. As part of IBM's compensation for the migration, [[IBM]] was given the rights to the [[Scientific Data Systems|Scientific Data Systems (SDS)]]/SAPE software, reportedly for a contract credit of $80,000.\n\nFive IBM engineers from the AI department<ref name=\"funding universe\">{{cite web |title=History of SAP AG |url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/sap-ag-history |accessdate=3 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"idch\">International Directory of Company Histories, Vol. 16. St James Press, 1997.</ref> ([[Dietmar Hopp]], [[Klaus Tschira]], [[Hans-Werner Hector]], [[Hasso Plattner]], and [[Claus Wellenreuther]], all from [[Mannheim]], Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg) were working on an enterprise-wide system based on this software, only to be told that it would no longer be necessary. Rather than abandoning the project, they decided to leave [[IBM]] Tech and start another company.<ref name=\"saphistory\">{{cite web|author=Staff|title=SAP History: From Start-Up Software Vendor to Global Market Leader|url=http://www.sap.com/corporate-en/about/our-company/history/index.html|accessdate=10 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1972, they founded the SAP {{lang|de|Systemanalyse und Programmentwicklung}} (\"System Analysis and Program Development\" / \"SAPD\") company, as a private partnership under the German Civil Code.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sap.com/corporate/en/company/history/1972-1980.html|title=The early years {{!}} SAP History {{!}} About SAP SE|website=SAP|language=en|access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref>\n\nTheir first client was the German branch of [[Imperial Chemical Industries]] in [[\u00d6stringen]],<ref>[http://www.sap.com/uk/about/success/casestudies/ici.epx SAP UK \u2013 ICI Success Story], Sap.com (1 January 1999); retrieved 24 April 2011.</ref> where they developed mainframe programs for payroll and accounting. Instead of storing the data on [[punch card]]s mechanically, as IBM did, they stored it locally in the Electronic System while using a common Logical database for all activities of Organization.{{clarify|date=April 2017}} Therefore, they called their software a [[real-time computing|real-time]] system, since there was no need to process the punch cards overnight (for this reason their flagship product carried an '''R''' in its name until the late 1990s). This first version was also a standalone software that could be offered to other interested parties.<ref>{{cite web|title=Standard Application Software for Real-time processing was developed|url=http://www.sap.com/corporate-en/about/our-company/history/1972-1981.html}}</ref>\n\n===Enterprise Resource Planning===\nIn 1973, the first commercial product was launched. SAP completes its first [[financial accounting]] system - RF. This system serves as the cornerstone in the ongoing development of other software modules of the system that will eventually bear the name SAP R/1.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThis offered a common system for multiple tasks. This permitted the use of a centralized data storage, improving the maintenance of data. From a technical point of view, therefore, a [[database]] was necessary.<ref name=\"ErfolgsfaktorenSAP\">{{cite web|url=http://chbeck.metapress.com/content/ph64048135784551|title=Vom Programmierb\u00fcro zum globalen Softwareproduzenten: Die Erfolgsfaktoren der SAP von der Gr\u00fcndung bis zum R/3-Boom, 1972 bis 1996|publisher=Chbeck.metapress.com|date=14 November 2008|access-date=27 March 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130128164657/http://chbeck.metapress.com/content/ph64048135784551|archive-date=28 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976, SAP GmbH Systeme, Anwendungen und Produkte in der Datenverarbeitung (\"Systems, Applications, and Products in Data Processing\") was founded as a sales and support subsidiary. Five years later, the private partnership was dissolved and its rights were passed on to SAP GmbH.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe headquarters moved the following year to [[Walldorf]], Germany. Three years later, in 1979, SAP launched [[SAP R/2]], expanding the capabilities of the system to other areas, such as material management and [[production planning]]. In 1981, SAP brought a re-designed product to market. However, SAP R/2 did not improve until the period between 1985 and 1990. SAP released the new [[SAP R/3]] in 1992. SAP developed and released several versions of R/3 through 1995. By the mid-1990s, SAP followed the trend from [[Mainframe computer|mainframe]] computing to [[client-server architecture|client/server architectures]]. The development of SAP's internet strategy with mySAP.com redesigned the concept of business processes (integration via Internet).<ref name=\"saphistory\" /> As a result, R/3 was replaced with the introduction of SAP ERP Central Component (ECC) 5.0 in 2004.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cipherbsc.com/sap-ecc-modules/|title=SAP ECC Modules - Cipher Business Solutions|last=Solutions|first=Cipher Business|publisher=Cipher Business Solutions|access-date=2017-03-29|language=en-US}}</ref> Architectural changes were also made to support an enterprise service architecture to transition customers to a services-oriented architecture. The latest version, [[SAP ERP]] 6.0, was released in 2006. SAP ERP 6.0 has since then been updated through SAP enhancement packs, the most recent: SAP enhancement package 8 for SAP ERP 6.0 in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/latest-version-sap-erp-available-ecc-60-ehp7-what-do-you-rakesh-singh|title=The latest version of SAP ERP available is SAP ECC 6.0 EHP7, What do you understand by ECC ?|date=2016-03-04|access-date=2018-02-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Corporate restructuring ===\nIn August 1988, SAP GmbH became SAP [[Aktiengesellschaft|AG]], and public trading started on 4 November 1988. Shares were listed on the [[Frankfurt Stock Exchange|Frankfurt]] and [[B\u00f6rse Stuttgart|Stuttgart stock exchanges]].<ref name=\"saphistory\"/> In 1995, SAP was included in the German stock index [[DAX]] and, on 22 September 2003, SAP was included in the [[STOXX Europe 50]].<ref>{{cite press release|publisher=Stoxx|title=STOXX Limited Announces Changes to its Blue-Chip Index Series|date=1 September 2003|url=http://www.whitehallresources.co.uk/stoxx-limited-announces-changes-to-its-blue-chip-index-series/|access-date=21 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021194441/http://www.whitehallresources.co.uk/stoxx-limited-announces-changes-to-its-blue-chip-index-series/|archive-date=21 October 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===SAP AG era===\nThe company's official name became ''SAP [[Aktiengesellschaft|AG]]'' (a public limited company) after the 2005 [[annual general meeting]].\n\nIn 2014-05-21, SAP AG announced during the Annual General Meeting of Shareholders held on the same day, 99% of the shareholder votes approved the conversion of legal form to a European stock corporation (Societas Europaea, SE) and at the same time, elected the first Supervisory Board of SAP SE. The conversion of the company's legal form would take place upon entry in the commercial register, expected to be in July 2014.<ref>[http://news.sap.com/2014/05/sap-annual-general-meeting-shareholders-2014/ Conversion of Legal Form to European Company (SE) Approved; SAP Shareholders Elect Jim Hagemann Snabe to Supervisory Board of SAP SE]</ref>\n<ref>[http://news.sap.com/2014/05/conversion-of-legal-form-to-european-company-se-approved-sap-shareholders-elect-jim-hagemann-snabe-to-supervisory-board-of-sap-se/ Conversion of Legal Form to European Company (SE) Approved; SAP Shareholders Elect Jim Hagemann Snabe to Supervisory Board of SAP SE]</ref>\n\n===SAP SE era===\nIn 2014-07-07, SAP announced it has turned its legal form to a European Company ([[Societas Europaea]], SE) in the same day. As a result, it German subsidiary was renamed to SAP Deutschland SE & Co. KG.<ref>[https://news.sap.com/2014/07/sap-se-now-european-company/ SAP Now European Company (SE)]</ref><ref>[http://news.sap.com/2014/07/sap-now-european-company-se/ SAP Now European Company (SE)]</ref> The conversion cost the company approximately \u20ac4 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224162330/https://www.sap.com/corporate-en/about/investors/investorservices/faq/index.html|title=Company Q & A|publisher=Investor Relations, SAP |accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Focus on cloud ===\nSince 2012, SAP has acquired several companies that sell [[cloud computing|cloud-based products]], with several multibillion-dollar acquisitions seen by analysts as an attempt to challenge competitor [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2012-05-22/sap-agrees-to-buy-ariba |title=SAP to Acquire Ariba for $4.3 Billion in Push Into Cloud |first1=Kenneth |last1=Wong |first2=Dina |last2=Bass |publisher=Bloomberg News |date=23 May 2012}}</ref> In 2014 SAP bought [[Concur Technologies]], a provider of cloud-based travel and expense management software, for $8.3 billion, SAP's most expensive purchase to that date.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/greatspeculations/2014/09/22/sap-to-acquire-concur-technologies-to-boost-cloud-sales |title=SAP To Acquire Concur Technologies To Boost Cloud Sales |newspaper=Forbes |date=22 September 2014}}</ref> Analysts' reactions to the purchase were mixed, with Thomas Becker of Commerzbank questioning whether Concur was the right choice for SAP, while Credit Suisse called the acquisition an \"aggressive\" move.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/sap-to-acquire-concur-technologies-1411076535 |title=SAP to Acquire Concur Technologies |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |first1=Neetha |last1=Mahadevan |first2=Stephan |last2=Doerner |date=19 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, IBM and SAP began a partnership to sell cloud-based services.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/ibm-and-sap-score-win-over-amazon-2014-10|title=IBM and SAP Score Win Over Amazon|publisher=BusinessInsider|date=14 October 2014}}</ref> Likewise, in 2015, SAP also partnered with [[Hewlett Packard Enterprise|HPE]] to provide secure hybrid cloud-based services running the SAP platform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www8.hp.com/us/en/hp-news/press-release.html?id=1982676#.WNdTf1XytEY|title=HP News - HP and SAP Accelerate Journey to SAP\u00ae S/4HANA on HP Helion Managed Cloud|publisher=Hewlett-Packard |language=en|access-date=2017-03-26}}</ref> Both HPE and IBM provide infrastructure services to SAP, and SAP runs its SAP HANA cloud solution on top. SAP has announced additional partnerships with Microsoft in order to give customers tools for data visualization, as well as improved mobile applications.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/05/19/microsoft-sap-strengthen-ties-with-mobile-data-cloud-partnership|title=Microsoft and SAP Strengthen Ties with Mobile, Data, Cloud Partnership|publisher=TechCrunch|date=19 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nSAP exceeded its revenue projections due to the expansion in its cloud business and the success of SAP HANA. The growth can also be partially attributed to the acquisitions of Concur and Fieldglass.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/greatspeculations/2015/01/22/sap-posts-strong-2014-results-cloud-business-to-drive-future-growth SAP Posts Strong 2014 Results, Cloud Business to Drive Future Growth ], Forbes, 22 January 2015</ref>\n\nThe company announced plans in 2016 to invest heavily into technology relating to [[Internet of things|Internet of Things]] (IoT) as part of a strategy to capitalize on the growth in that market. For that purpose, \u20ac2 billion is planned for investment in relevant sectors by the end of 2020.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2016/09/28/sap-invest-billion-internet-things-2020/|title=SAP Plans to Invest $2.2 Billion in the Internet of Things by 2020|agency=Reuters|publisher=Fortune|access-date=2017-07-17}}</ref> SAP will also launch a new product line called SAP IoT, which \"will combine large amounts of data from things connected to the Internet with machine learning and SAP's real-time database S/4 HANA.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn January 29, 2019, SAP announced plans to cut approximately 4,000 positions at the company in a strategic plan to shift to more modern cloud-based technologies such as [[blockchain]], [[quantum computing]], [[machine learning]], [[Internet of Things]], and [[artificial intelligence]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Miller |first=Ron |url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/01/29/sap-job-cuts-prove-harsh-realities-of-enterprise-transformation/ |title= SAP job cuts prove harsh realities of enterprise transformation |work=[[TechCrunch]] |date=2019-01-29 |accessdate=2019-01-29 }}</ref>\n\n== Finances ==\nFor the fiscal year 2017, SAP reported earnings of EUR\u20ac4 billion, with an annual revenue of EUR\u20ac23.5 billion, an increase of 6.3% over the previous fiscal cycle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wallstreet-online.de/aktien/sap-aktie/bilanz|title=SAP Bilanz, Gewinn und Umsatz {{!}} SAP Gesch\u00e4ftsbericht {{!}} 716460|website=wallstreet-online.de|access-date=2018-12-04}}</ref> SAP's shares traded at over US$105 per share, and its market capitalization was valued at US$128 billion in December 2018. This makes SAP the most valuable company in Germany.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/SAP/key-statistics?p=SAP&.tsrc=fin-srch|title=SAP Key Statistics {{!}} SAP SE ADS Stock - Yahoo Finance|website=finance.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-04}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable float-left\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n!Year\n!Revenue<br />in bn. EUR\u20ac\n!Net income<br />in bn. EUR\u20ac\n!Total Assets<br />in bn. EUR\u20ac\n!Employees\n|-\n|2013\n|16.815\n|3.326\n|27.094\n|66,572\n|-\n|2014\n|17.560\n|3.280\n|38.507\n|74,406\n|-\n|2015\n|20.793\n| 3.064\n|41.390\n|76,986\n|-\n|2016\n|22.062\n|3.646\n|44.277\n|84,183\n|-\n|2017\n|23.461\n|4.018\n|42.497\n|88,543\n|}\n\n==Acquisitions==\n{