nternational AG || Dec 2001 || Invoice Processing || Germany ||\n|-\n| 11 || COPA GmbH || Nov 2001 || Beverage industry consulting || Germany ||\n|-\n| 10 || Infinite Data Structures || May 2001 || Trade Management / CRM || USA ||\n|-\n| 9 || Toptier || Mar 2001 || Enterprise Information Portal and Integration Infrastructure || USA || ~$400m\n|-\n| 8 || Prescient Consulting || Feb 2000 || Consulting services || USA ||\n|-\n| 7 || In-Q-My Technologies GmbH || 2000 || J2EE Server || Bulgaria ||\n|-\n| 6 || Campbell Software || 1999 || Workforce Management || USA ||\n|-\n| 5 || AMC Development || 1998 || Call Center telephony integration software || USA ||\n|-\n| 4 || OFEK-Tech || 1998 || Warehousing and distribution centre software || Israel ||\n|-\n| 3 || Kiefer & Veittinger || 1997 || Sales force Applications || Germany ||\n|-\n| 2 || Dacos || 1996 || Retail solution || Germany ||\n|-\n| 1 || Steeb || 1991 || Software and Consulting Services || Germany ||\n|-\n|}\n\n==Business and markets==\n{{As of|2016}}, SAP is the world's third largest software and programming company.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/global2000/list/#industry:Software%20%26%20Programming |title=The World's Biggest Public Companies, Software & Programming |work=Forbes |accessdate=21 October 2016}}</ref> The corporation operates in Europe, Asia, Africa, the Middle East, North America, and South America.<ref>{{cite web|title=Worldwide Office Directory of SAP|url=http://www.sap.com/directory/main.html}}</ref>\n\nSAP focuses on 25 industries and six industry sectors: process industries, discrete industries, consumer industries, service industries, financial services and public services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sap.com/solution.html|title=Business in Brief: Markets|publisher=SAP|access-date=15 October 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130425005304/http://www54.sap.com/solution.html|archive-date=25 April 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It offers integrated product sets for large enterprises,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sap.com/germany/company/investor/reports/gb2006/en/business/midmarket-solutions-2.html#1|title=Midmarket Solutions: SAP ALL-IN-ONE \u2013 Solutions for mid-size companies|work=Annual Report 2006|publisher=SAP |access-date=15 October 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011185959/http://www.sap.com/germany/company/investor/reports/gb2006/en/business/midmarket-solutions-2.html#1|archive-date=11 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> mid-sized companies and small businesses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sap.com/germany/company/investor/reports/gb2006/en/business/industry-solutions.html|title=Industry Solutions: Innovation \u2013 One Industry at a Time|work=Annual Report 2006|publisher=SAP |access-date=15 October 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011100833/http://www.sap.com/germany/company/investor/reports/gb2006/en/business/industry-solutions.html|archive-date=11 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Enterprise service-oriented architecture==\n[[Service-oriented architecture]] has been incorporated into the SAP ERP ([[Enterprise Resource Planning]]) system and other products defined within the SAP Enterprise Services Architecture (Enterprise SOA).\n\n===Enterprise SOA=== <!-- Anchor from redirect of [SAP Enterprise Services Architecture]; caution. -->\n''SAP Enterprise Service Oriented Architecture'' (or ''Enterprise SOA'') is SAP SE's [[service-oriented architecture]] implementation.<ref>[http://global.sap.com/platform/soa/adoptionprogram.epx ''SAP - Enterprise Service-Oriented Architecture: Adoption Program''] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20140113103954/http://global.sap.com/platform/soa/adoptionprogram.epx |date=13 January 2014 }}, global.sap.com; accessed 27 May 2015.</ref> Enterprise SOA is enabled by the [[SAP NetWeaver]] platform and builds on the benefits of [[Web service]]s. SAP has positioned Enterprise SOA to deliver the benefits offered by service-oriented architecture, including enabling both flexibility and business efficiency. SAP markets Enterprise SOA(Service-oriented architecture) as a cost-effective way of adding new applications to existing infrastructure.<ref>\"When Does a Web Service Become an Enterprise Service?\" by Dr Franz-Josef Fritz (SAP AG), ''SAP Insider'', April\u2013May\u2013June 2004.</ref> SAP Solutions that currently use Enterprise SOA are [[mySAP CRM]], [[mySAP ERP]], and [[mySAP SRM]].\n\n==Partnerships==\nSAP partners include Global Services Partners with cross-industry multinational consulting capabilities,<ref>[http://go.sap.com/partner.html SAP \u2013 Global & Local Partner Directories: Global Services Partners]. SAP AG. Retrieved 7 July 2011.</ref> Global Software Partners providing integrated products that complement SAP Business Suite solutions,<ref>[http://go.sap.com/partner.html SAP \u2013 Global & Local Partner Directories: Global Software Partners]. Sap.com (30 June 2009). Retrieved on 7 July 2011.</ref> and Global Technology Partners providing user companies with a wide range of products to support SAP technology, including vendors of hardware, database, storage systems, networks, and mobile computing technology.<ref>[http://go.sap.com/partner.html SAP \u2013 Global & Local Partner Directories: Global Technology Partners], go.sap.com; retrieved 7 July 2011.</ref>\n\nExtensions partners are companies which provide functionality that complements SAP product capabilities. Their products are certified, sold, and supported by SAP. These partner companies include [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]], [[CA Technologies]], [[GK Software]],<ref>[http://www.news-sap.com/sap-offers-extended-global-reseller-agreement-with-gk-software/ SAP Offers Retailers in North America a Full Range of Store Solutions to Optimize Their Businesses Through Extended Global Reseller Agreement With GK Software]. sap-news.com (28 May 2013). Retrieved on 22 May 2015.</ref> [[Hewlett-Packard]], [[IDS Scheer]], [[Mendix]],<ref>[https://www.mendix.com/press/mendix-announces-global-reseller-agreement-with-sap-providing-enterprises-low-code-development-for-building-web-and-mobile-apps-at-speed-and-scale/ Mendix Announces Global Reseller Agreement with SAP, Providing Enterprises Low-Code Development for Building Enterprise Apps at Speed and Scale]. Mendix.com (26 September 2017). Retrieved on 28 March 2018.</ref> [[OpenText]],<ref>[https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/opentext-named-solution-extension-partner-of-the-year-and-sap-database-and-data-management-partner-of-the-year-in-2017-sap-pinnacle-awards-300458320.html OpenText Named Solution Extension Partner of the Year and SAP Database and Data Management Partner of the Year in 2017 SAP\u00ae Pinnacle Awards]. prnewswire.com (16 May 2017). Retrieved on 09 March 2018.</ref> [[Knoa Software]], and BackOffice Associates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scn.sap.com/community/solution-extensions|title=Solution Extensions {{!}} Digital Jouney {{!}} SAP|publisher=SAP|language=en|access-date=2018-02-01}}</ref>\n\nSAP has also partnered with [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] to work on the mobile experience for SAP enterprise customers. As part of the partnership, a new [[SAP HANA Cloud Platform]] SDK would be delivered exclusively for [[iOS]]. As a result, developers can build applications based on the SAP HANA Cloud Platform for the [[iPhone]] and [[iPad]] devices. The partnership was announced in May 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sap.com/apple-sap-partner-to-revolutionize-work-on-iphone-ipad/|title=Apple & SAP Partner to Revolutionize Work on iPhone & iPad|date=2016-05-05|publisher=SAP News Center|access-date=2017-09-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, SAP announced a three-year partnership \"Embrace\" with [[Microsoft]] that should allow its clients to move their business process into the cloud.[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sap-results/sap-in-three-year-cloud-partnership-with-microsoft-idUSKBN1X00DR]\n\n==SAP PartnerEdge==\nSAP products for small businesses and midsize companies are delivered through its global partner network. The SAP PartnerEdge programme, SAP's partner programme, offers a set of business enablement resources and program benefits to help partners including value-added resellers (VARs) and independent software vendors (ISVs) be profitable and successful in implementing, selling, marketing, developing and delivering SAP products to a broad range of customers.<ref>[http://www1.sap.com/about/press/factsheets/smb.epx SAP \u2013 SAP Solutions for Small Businesses and Midsize Companies: Press Fact Sheet, July 2007] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026210602/http://www.sap.com/about/press/factsheets/smb.epx |date=26 October 2007 }}. SAP.com; retrieved 7 July 2011.</ref>\n\n==Communities==\n[[SAP Community Network]] (SCN) is a community of SAP customers, partners, employees, and influencers \u2013 typically in roles such as: developers, consultants, integrators, and business analysts \u2013 who gain and share knowledge about [[ABAP]], Java, .NET, SOA, and other technologies, plus analytics and dashboards, business process best practices, cloud, mobile, big data, and a range of other topics via blogs, discussion forums, downloads and code samples, training materials, and a technical library.<ref>[http://go.sap.com/community.html SAP \u2013 Communities]. go.sap.com; retrieved 7 July 2011.</ref>\n\n==Organization==\n{{primary sources|section|date=July 2016}}\nSAP uses a two-tier structure of boards, with an [[executive board]] and a [[supervisory board]]. As of 2016, members of the executive board were [[Bill McDermott]] (former [[chief executive officer|CEO]] and Chairman, joined in 2008), Robert Enslin (2014), Bernd Leukert (2014), Luka Mucic ([[Chief financial officer|CFO]], 2014), Michael Kleinemeier (2015), Stefan Ries (2016), Steve Singh (2016) and Gerhard Oswald (1996).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sap.com/corporate-en/about/our-company/our-boards/executive-board.html|title=SAP Executive Board|publisher=SAP}}</ref> Juergen Mueller will join the executive board in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/chief-innovation-officer-juergen-mueller-to-join-sap-se-board-300738290.html|title=Chief Innovation Officer Juergen Mueller to Join SAP SE Board|publisher=PR Newswire}}</ref> In October 2019, [[Jennifer Morgan]] and {{ill|Christian Klein|de|Christian Klein (Manager)}} were appointed as co-[[Chief executive officer|CEO]]s of SAP.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sap.com/2019/10/sap-set-course-future-next-generation-leadership/|title=SAP Sets Course with Next-Generation Leadership Team {{!}} SAP News|date=2019-10-10|website=SAP News Center|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref>\n\nFunctional units of SAP are split across different organizational units for R&D needs, field activities and customer support. SAP Labs are mainly responsible for product development whereas the field organizations spread across each country are responsible for field activities such sales, marketing and consulting. Headquarters is responsible for overall management as well as core engineering activities related to product development. Worldwide customer support is not provided by the field organizations but by a unified organization called Active Global Support (AGS).<ref>{{cite web|title=SAP launches Global Support Center|url=http://global.sap.com/corporate-en/news.epx?PressID=3042}}</ref>\n\n== SAP Labs ==\n{{primary sources|section|date=October 2017}}\n'''SAP Labs''' are R&D locations that develop and improve SAP core products. SAP Labs are strategically located in high-tech clusters around the globe.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable, wikitable floatright\" border=\"1\"\n|+Locations of SAP Labs\n|-\n!Country\n!Main location(s)\n|-\n|[[Germany]]\n|[[Walldorf]]/Rot, [[Markdorf]], [[Berlin]]\n|-\n|[[United States]]\n|[[Silicon Valley]]\n|-\n|[[India]]\n|[[Bangalore]]\n|-\n|[[China]]\n|[[Shanghai]]\n|-\n|[[Brazil]]\n|[[S\u00e3o Leopoldo]]\n|-\n|[[Bulgaria]]\n|[[Sofia]]\n|-\n|[[Canada]]\n|[[Vancouver]], [[Montreal]], [[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]]\n|-\n|[[South Korea]]\n|[[Seoul]]\n|-\n|[[Vietnam]]\n|[[Ho Chi Minh City]]\n|-\n|[[Israel]]\n|[[Ra'anana]]\n|-\n|CIS\n|[[Moscow]]\n|-\n|[[France]]\n|[[Paris]], [[Sophia Antipolis]]\n|-\n|[[Ireland]]\n|[[Dublin]]\n|-\n|[[Hungary]]\n|[[Budapest]]\n|-\n|[[Slovakia]]\n|[[Bratislava]]\n|-\n|[[Czech Republic]]\n|[[Brno]]\n|-\n|[[Poland]]\n|[[Gliwice]]\n|}\n\nThe four most prominent labs of SAP SE are located in Germany, India, China and the US. Labs Walldorf was founded in 1972 and became SAP's primary location. At the beginning, the focus of SAP's expansion was entering highly developed IT markets; in 1993 Palo Alto became a part of SAP Labs. Aiming to acquire talented employees, SAP opened another lab in Bangalore in 2003.\n\nAmong the latest SAP Labs are labs in Czech Republic, Slovakia and Poland. All three labs have been established in 2016. The labs in India are now the largest labs outside Germany.\n\nIn order to manage SAP Labs, '''SAP Labs Network (SLN)''' was created. SLN is a global unit that manages regional Labs and shares best business practices. It coordinates and distributes development projects among individual SAP Labs locations, accelerates product delivery, gives SAP full access to talent, and drives SAP corporate strategy regarding innovation and business growth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sap.com/corporate/en/company/innovation/sap-labs.html|title=R&D Locations {{!}} SAP Labs {{!}} About SAP SE|publisher=SAP|access-date=2016-04-29}}</ref>\n\n==SAP User Groups==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=October 2017}}\n'''SAP User Groups''' are independent, nonprofit organizations of SAP customers and SAP partners. They serve as communications channel for their members towards SAP and for SAP towards the markets. The Americas' SAP Users' Group (ASUG) is the company's largest user group, with 100,000 individuals at 3,800 companies. ASUG members are professionals who work in more than 17 industries. Many are technical and business process experts in the SAP ecosystem; they have varied levels of experience, and come from small businesses to global corporations, as well as universities. In 2007, the SAP User Group Executive Network (SUGEN) was established.\n\nSAP provoked controversy and frustration among its users in 2008 by raising the cost of its maintenance contracts. The issue was the subject of intense discussion among user groups.<ref>[http://www.computerworlduk.com/management/it-business/supplier-relations/news/index.cfm?newsid=10632 SAP faces user wrath over price hikes]. Computerworlduk.com. Retrieved on 7 July 2011.</ref>\n\n==SAP Cloud Platform==\nSAP Cloud Platform is SAP's platform-as-a-service (PaaS)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cloudplatform.sap.com/index.html}}</ref> that is used to deliver in-memory capabilities and microservices for building and extending, mobile-enabled cloud applications. The infrastructure is offered through a global network of SAP managed data centers. SAP Cloud Platform is an open platform-as-a-service, which includes the in-memory SAP HANA database management system, connects to both on premises and cloud-based systems running SAP or other third-party software and relies on open standards, like Java, JavaScript, Node.js and Cloud Foundry for integration options.\n\nSAP Cloud Platform is promoted to build and extend business applications with rapid innovation cycles. SAP and Apple Inc. partnered to develop mobile applications on iOS using cloud-based software development kits (SDKs) for the SAP Cloud Platform. SAP founding development partners<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.insidesap.com.au/winners-of-2015-sap-pinnacle-awards-announced/|title=Winners of 2015 SAP Pinnacle Awards announced - Inside SAP|website=www.insidesap.com.au|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-04}}</ref> for their Cloud Platform include [[Accenture]], Celonis, [[EnterpriseAlumni]], and [[Walmart]].\n\nSAP Cloud Platform is based on open source technology, developed & supported in partnership with SUSE. The company is also in partnership with Cloud Foundry for a beta offering of SAP Cloud Platform that enables customers to test out and give feedback for the functionalities coming with Cloud Foundry.\n\n==SAP S/4HANA==\nIn 2015, the company launched S/4HANA, the newest generation of the SAP Business Suite. It was written natively for the [[SAP HANA]] platform. It offers cloud, on-premises and hybrid deployment options to customers, with its benefits including a smaller data footprint, higher throughput, faster analytics and faster access to data. It also allows existing SAP Business Suite customers to upgrade to this product from SAP Business Suite.<ref>{{cite web|title=Answers on SAP upgradation to SAP S/4HANA|url=http://news.sap.com/what-is-sap-s4hana-13-questions-answered/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, SAP introduced SAP HANA, Express Edition which is meant to run on personal computers or on cloud computing platforms for students and other small-scale developers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/sap-aims-to-court-more-hana-developers-launches-express-edition/ |title=SAP aims to court more HANA developers, launches express edition |publisher=ZDNet |date=16 September 2016 |accessdate=19 November 2016 |author=Larry Dignan}}</ref>\n\n==SAP Store==\nSAP launched the SAP store in March 2015 as its principal e-commerce property to allow customers to buy its products directly on the Web rather than through traditional sales channels. Customers can purchase free trials or starter editions and can pay by credit card or PayPal.\n\n==SAP App Center==\nLaunched in 2016, the SAP App Center is an online [[app store|application marketplace]] for third-party applications that integrate with and extend SAP products. Applications are available for free, as well as via yearly or monthly subscription models. Applications available range from integrations with content management software to mobile approval management and payment platforms. As of July 2018, it features over 1,500 applications.\n\n==Conferences==\nSAP has two annual conferences:\n* SAPPHIRE is SAP's customer-facing event, where it generally announces major product changes and strategic direction. It is typically held in the spring in North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.v3.co.uk/v3-uk/news/2154366/sap-unveils-successfactors-cloud-computing-roadmap-squares-oracle|title=SAP unveils SuccessFactors cloud computing roadmap as it squares up to Oracle|publisher=V3.co.uk|accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internetnews.com/ent-news/article.php/2223461|title=SAP Rolls Out Updates at SAPPHIRE|publisher=InternetNews|date=17 June 2003|accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n* SAP TechEd is the company's more technical conference, aimed at SAP's ecosystem of consultants and software development partners.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2005-09-22/bangalore/27845182_1_teched-key-theme-solutions|title=SAP TechEd '05 in Bangalore|publisher=Articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com|date=22 September 2005|accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcworld.com/article/207317/sap_teched_to_go_deep_on_mobility_ondemand.html|title=SAP TechEd to Go Deep on Mobility|publisher=Pcworld.com|date=8 October 2010|accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref> SAP TechEd has been held annually since 1995.\n\n==Competitive landscape==\nSAP competitors are primarily in the [[enterprise resource planning]] software industry. In this field, [[Oracle Corporation]] is SAP's major competitor. SAP also competes in the customer relationship management, marketing & sales software, manufacturing, warehousing & industrial software, and supply chain management & logistics software sectors.<ref>{{cite news|author=Staff|title=SAP Competitors|url=http://www.hoovers.com/company-information/cs/competition.sap_se.48cbdfcd173cadff.html}}</ref>\n\nOracle Corporation filed [[Oracle Corp. v. SAP AG|a lawsuit against SAP]] for malpractice and unfair competition in the California courts in 2007. SAP lost the case in 2010 and was ordered to pay $1.3&nbsp;billion, which was cited as the largest [[copyright infringement]] judgment in history.<ref>{{cite news|title=SAP to pay Oracle $1.3 billion in landmark decision|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/11/24/us-oracle-sap-idUSTRE6AL4IN20101124|publisher=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=2 October 2015|first=Dan|last=Levine|date=23 November 2010}}</ref> The verdict was overturned in 2011,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/02/technology/oracle-verdict-against-sap-is-overturned.html|title=Oracle Verdict Against SAP Is Overturned|publisher=Associated Press|date=1 September 2011|accessdate=12 January 2015}}.</ref> and the lawsuit was finally settled in 2014 for $356.7&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2014/11/13/technology/13reuters-oracle-sap-se-settlement.html|title=Oracle, SAP Settle Long-Running TomorrowNow Lawsuit|publisher=Reuters|date=13 November 2014|accessdate=14 August 2015}}.</ref>\n\nThe resulting pressure saw SAP and SUGEN (SAP User Group Executive Network) agree to a major benchmarking exercise to prove the value of the new support pricing policy to customers. In December 2009, SAP delayed its Enterprise Support price rises until agreement had been reached on the benchmarks and KPIs (Key Performance Indicators).<ref>[http://www.computerworlduk.com/management/infrastructure/applications/news/index.cfm?newsId=17810 SAP delays Enterprise Support price rises]. Computerworlduk.com; retrieved 7 July 2011.</ref>\n\nIn January 2010, SAP reversed its direction on Enterprise Support and reintroduced its standard support package for customers. The move to reinstate standard support \u2013 at 18 percent of annual license fees, \"will enable all customers to choose the option that best meets their requirements\", the company said.<ref>[http://www.computerworlduk.com/management/infrastructure/applications/news/index.cfm?newsId=18318 SAP does U-turn on Enterprise Support]. Computerworlduk.com; retrieved 7 July 2011.</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, SAP acquired German software company [[Hybris (company)|Hybris]] for eCommerce capabilities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.eweek.com/it-management/sap-closes-deal-to-acquire-mdm-maker-hybris|title=SAP Closes Deal to Acquire MDM Maker Hybris|publisher=eWEEK|access-date=2018-02-01|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>[http://www.informationweek.com/applications/sap-buys-hybris-gains-customer-experience-power/d/d-id/1111073 \"SAP buys Hybris, gains customer experience, power\"], informationweek.com; accessed 27 May 2015.</ref>\n\n==Philanthropic efforts==\nSAP has donated several millions of dollars to a variety of global health causes including the [[Product Red]] campaign and the [[Global Fund]].<ref>{{cite web|title=(RED) Partners|url=http://www.joinred.com/partners/#!/shopred/sap|work=(RED)|publisher=The ONE Campaign|date=14 October 2012|access-date=27 May 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524044206/http://www.joinred.com/partners/#!/shopred/sap|archive-date=24 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidephilanthropy.com/tech-philanthropy/2014/10/8/what-this-giant-software-company-is-doing-to-advance-global.html |title=What This Giant Software Company Is Doing to Advance Global Health |publisher=Inside Philanthropy |date=8 October 2014 |accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref> In addition, SAP has distributed free software in South Africa as part of an effort towards developing future markets there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.triplepundit.com/2013/08/business-case-strategic-philanthropy |title=The Business Case for Strategic Philanthropy |publisher= TriplePundit |date=8 August 2013 |accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref> The company also encourages employees to volunteer through social sabbaticals, sending teams of people to different countries to aid non-profits. SAP employees have volunteered in China, India, Brazil, and South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/ernst-young-sap-corporate-volunteering |title=How EY and SAP are championing corporate volunteering |publisher=The Guardian |date=11 February 2014 |accessdate = 13 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Sponsorships==\n\nThe [[SAP Arena]] opened in Mannheim in 2005, and is the home of the [[Adler Mannheim]] ice hockey team and [[Rhein-Neckar L\u00f6wen]] handball team. Since 2013, the company is name sponsor of the [[SAP Center]] at San Jose, California. The team also sponsors the Formula One racing team [[McLaren]], German football team [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim]], NFL teams the [[New York Giants]] and [[New York Jets]], the [[City Football Group]], and eSports squad [[Team Liquid]]. It was the title sponsor of the Formula One [[United States Grand Prix]] from 2000 to 2002.\n\nSAP ambassadors include German tennis player [[Angelique Kerber]], German eventing rider [[Ingrid Klimke]], and South African golfers [[Ernie Els]], [[Gary Player]] and [[Branden Grace]].\n\n==Autism hiring==\nSAP also engages in outreach activities within its company. In 2013, the company launched an initiative to hire employees with autism and [[Asperger syndrome]], citing their undervalued ability to contribute to its workforce. SAP aims to compose 1% of its workforce with individuals with autism by the year 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-22621829 |title=SAP in autism recruitment drive |publisher=BBC News |date=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Bribery and corruption ==\n=== East African allegations ===\n\nIn February 2019, SAP was accused of \u2018improper conduct\u2019 linked to state contracts in Kenya and Tanzania. An anonymous whistle-blower claims, through a firm of attorneys, that SAP used Twenty Third Century Systems (TTCS) to bribe officials at the Tanzania Ports Authority (TPA) to win a US$6.6-million enterprise resource planning software tender that involved the provision of software licenses and services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcentral.co.za/sap-eoh-affiliate-ttcs-caught-up-in-bribery-allegations/87871/|title=SAP, EOH affiliate TTCS caught up in bribery allegations - TechCentral|website=techcentral.co.za|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n\n=== South African allegations ===\n\nIn July 2017, allegations were made that SAP had been involved in business transactions with the controversial and politically influential [[Gupta family]] in South Africa. SAP was accused of paying CAD House, a Gupta-controlled company, R100 million in order to secure a [[Transnet]] deal. SAP denied the allegations, claiming that the money was paid as \"an extension of the sales force\", despite CAD House having no prior SAP experience.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/guptaleaks-software-giant-paid-gupta-front-r100m-kickbacks-for-state-business-20170711|title=#GuptaLeaks: Software giant paid Gupta front R100m 'kickbacks' for state business|publisher=News24|access-date=2017-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://amabhungane.co.za/article/2017-07-11-guptaleaks-software-giant-sap-paid-gupta-front-r100m-kickbacks-for-state-business|title=amaBhungane - #GuptaLeaks: Software giant SAP paid Gupta front R100m \"kickbacks\" for state business|publisher=amabhungane.co.za|language=en|access-date=2017-07-11}}</ref>\n\nThe Guptas' dealings with SAP were revealed in a widely publicized e-mail leak.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fin24.com/Economy/guptas-just-tip-of-sas-corruption-ice-berg-saftu-20170711|title=Guptas just tip of SA's corruption ice-berg - Saftu|publisher=Fin24|access-date=2017-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/business/184559/software-giant-pulled-into-gupta-saga-with-allegations-of-r100-million-kickbacks/|title=Software giant pulled into Gupta saga with allegations of R100 million kickbacks|access-date=2017-07-11|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAs a consequence of the allegations, SAP launched an investigation that led to four of its South African managers being placed on administrative leave along with the seizure of their mobile phones and computers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d8d693c0-67d8-11e7-8526-7b38dcaef614|title=Germany's SAP to investigate South Africa kickback allegations|newspaper=Financial Times}}</ref> Claas Kuehnemann was named as acting managing director for Africa while the investigation continued.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=163367|title=SAP names Kuehnemann as acting MD |publisher=ITWeb Technology News|access-date=2017-07-17}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 October 2017, SAP announced that it had voluntarily reported itself to the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] for a possible violation of US law, including the [[Foreign Corrupt Practices Act]], related to the South African bribery allegations. SAP's own investigation, conducted by law firm [[Baker McKenzie]], revealed that SAP had paid $7.7 million in commissions to third-parties linked to the Gupta family while securing contracts worth $48 million with Transnet and [[Eskom]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sap.com/sap-provides-update-on-ongoing-investigation-into-its-south-africa-business/|title=SAP Provides Update on Ongoing Investigation into Its South Africa Business|date=26 October 2017|publisher=SAP News Center|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026143054/https://news.sap.com/sap-provides-update-on-ongoing-investigation-into-its-south-africa-business/|archive-date=26 October 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2017/10/26/sap-south-africa-gupta-doj-sec-corruption/|title=SAP Is Being Investigated by the U.S. Over a Major International Kickback Scandal|last=Meyer|first=David|date=26 October 2017|publisher=Fortune |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026143214/http://fortune.com/2017/10/26/sap-south-africa-gupta-doj-sec-corruption/|archive-date=26 October 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2017-10-26-us-justice-department-launches-investigation-into-sap-gupta-dealings|title=US justice department launches investigation into SAP-Gupta dealings|date=26 October 2017|newspaper=Mail and Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026143251/https://mg.co.za/article/2017-10-26-us-justice-department-launches-investigation-into-sap-gupta-dealings|archivedate=26 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Panamanian bribery ===\n\nIn May 2015, SAP agreed to pay $3.9 million to settle [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] civil charges over a former executive's scheme to bribe Panama government officials in order to win lucrative technology contracts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sap-se-sec-idUSKCN0VA3HW|title=#PanamaBribery: SAP settles with SEC over Panama bribery scheme|publisher=Reuters|access-date=2017-07-14}}</ref><ref>https://www.sec.gov/news/pressrelease/2016-17.html</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n* [[List of ERP software packages]]\n* [[List of SAP products]]\n* [[SAP Center]], an indoor arena in San Jose, California that bears the company's name via a sponsorship contract\n* [[SAP implementation]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|SAP}}\n* {{official website}}\n{{Finance links\n| name = SAP SE\n| symbol = SAP\n| sec_cik = 1000184\n| hoovers = SAP_AG.48cbdfcd173cadff\n}}\n\n{{SAP AG}}\n{{Euro Stoxx 50 Companies}}\n{{DAX companies}}\n{{Philadelphia Corporations}}\n{{Major software companies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sap Se}}\n[[Category:SAP SE| ]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:Banking software companies]]\n[[Category:Cloud computing providers]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]]\n[[Category:Software companies established in 1972]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Frankfurt Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:CRM software companies]]\n[[Category:ERP software companies]]\n[[Category:German brands]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in Germany]]\n[[Category:OpenTravel Alliance]]\n[[Category:Software companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Societates Europaeae]]\n[[Category:Companies in the Euro Stoxx 50]]\n[[Category:1972 in computer science]]\n[[Category:1978 in computer science]]\n", "name_user": "Chomsnl1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAcquisitions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SAP_SE"}
{"title_page": "J. K. Scott", "text_new": "Really good punter that wins the superbowl\n| statvalue3    = 44.3\n| statlabel4    = Inside 20\n| statvalue4    = 48\n| statlabel5    = Longest punt\n| statvalue5    = 67\n| nflnew        = jkscott/2560868\n}}\n'''John Kimball Scott''' (born October 30, 1995) is an [[American football]] [[Punter (football)|punter]] for the [[Green Bay Packers]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]], and was selected by the Packers in the fifth round of the [[2018 NFL Draft]].\n\n==Early years==\nScott attended and played [[high school football]] at [[Mullen High School]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/Player/JK-Scott-32788/high-school-53129/ |title=JK Scott, J.K. Mullen , Kicker |website=247Sports  |access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref> He received offers from Arizona, Colorado, and Notre Dame but ultimately accepted Alabama's offer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/Recruitment/JK-Scott-34567/RecruitInterests/ |title=JK Scott Recruit Interests |website=247sports.com |access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\nScott converted 13 of 25 field goals with a long of 59 yards and 69 of 71-point after attempts during his high school career, he also had 4,758 kick off yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.maxpreps.com/m/athlete/jk-scott/HOU2jPiFEeKZ5AAmVebBJg/football/stats.htm |title=JK Scott MaxPreps Interests |website=Maxpreps.com |access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nScott attended the [[University of Alabama]], where he played on the [[Alabama Crimson Tide football]] team under head coach [[Nick Saban]] from 2014 to 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rolltide.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3950|title=Alabama Crimson Tide : JK Scott|work=RollTide.com|accessdate=May 12, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512004310/https://rolltide.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3950|archivedate=May 12, 2018}}</ref> He was a consensus first-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] selection in 2014 and was chosen as an [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] by ''[[Sporting News]]'', ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', [[ESPN]], and ''[[USA Today]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.secsports.com/article/12000565/the-2014-ap-all-sec-football-team|title=The 2014 AP All-SEC football team}}</ref> He was also named first-team All-SEC for his performances in the 2016 season, and was part of the 2015 and 2017 Alabama Crimson Tide national championship teams.\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"12\" style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Alabama Crimson Tide|color=white}};\" |'''Alabama Crimson Tide'''\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|GP !! colspan=\"15\"|Punting\n|-\n! Punts !! Yds !! Lng !! Avg !! Blk !! In 20 !! TB !! FC !! Ret !! RetY\n|-\n! [[2014 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2014]]\n| 13 || 55 || 2,640 || 73 || 48.0 || 0 || 31 || 5 || 19 || 12 || 83\n|-\n! [[2015 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2015]]\n| 15 || 70 || 3,094 || 59 || 44.2 || 1 || 25 || 9 || 18 || 27 || 279\n|-\n! [[2016 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2016]]\n| 15 || 64 || 3,020 || 66 || 47.2 || 1 || 25 || 12 || 15 || 20 || 213\n|-\n! [[2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2017]]\n| 14 || 54 || 2,320 || 64 || 43.0 || 1 || 27 || 4 || 27 || 5 || 36\n|-\n! Total || 57 || 243 || 11,074 || 73 || 45.6 || 3 || 108 || 30 || 79 || 64 || 611\n|-\n| colspan=\"12\"|<small>Source: [https://rolltide.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3950 RollTide.com]</small>\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\n[[File:JK Scott 6 Packers training camp 2019 (cropped).jpg|180px|thumb|left|Scott during 2019 training camp.]]\n{{external media\n| video1 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000929991/packers-select-jk-scott-no-172-in-the-2018-nfl-draft Scott gets drafted by Green Bay]\n}}\n\n{{NFL predraft\n| height ft    = 6\n| height in    = 5\u215d\n| weight       = 208\n| dash         = 4.83\n| ten split    = 1.68\n| twenty split = 2.81\n| shuttle      = 4.41\n| cone drill   = 7.28\n| vertical     = 30\u00bd\n| broad ft     = 9\n| broad in     = 6\n| bench        = \n| wonderlic    = \n| arm span     = 33\u215b\n| hand span    = 9\u215b\n| note         = All values from [[2018 NFL Draft | NFL Draft]]<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.nfl.com/prospects/jk-scott?id=32462018-0002-5600-7115-5dafcb9a6922 | title = NFL Draft Prospect Profile \u2013 JK Scott | publisher = National Football League | date = March 1, 2018 | access-date = March 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.draftscout.com/ratings/pyrnotes.php?pyid=130760&draftyear=2018&genpos=P | title = Alabama P JK Scott : 2018 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile | work = NFLDraftScout.com | accessdate = May 12, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\nScott was selected by the [[Green Bay Packers]] with the 172nd overall pick in the fifth round of the [[2018 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.packers.com/news-and-events/article-draft/article-1/packers-draft-punter-jk-scott-in-fifth-round/3b71fd75-ae1b-461a-8da1-36acf4fcb21c|title=Packers draft punter JK Scott in fifth round|last=Hodkiewicz|first=Wes|work=Packers.com|date=April 28, 2018|accessdate=April 28, 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504204634/http://www.packers.com/news-and-events/article-draft/article-1/packers-draft-punter-jk-scott-in-fifth-round/3b71fd75-ae1b-461a-8da1-36acf4fcb21c|archivedate=May 4, 2018}}</ref> He was the second of four punters to be selected that year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2018/draft.htm |title=2018 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=August 10, 2018}}</ref> On May 4, 2018, he signed a contract with the Packers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.packers.com/news-and-events/article-roster-moves/article-1/packers-announce-roster-moves/82a1bed1-0ef9-4e1d-895c-361b72eb4b5f|title=Packers announce roster moves|work=Packers.com|date=May 4, 2018|accessdate=May 4, 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504204338/http://www.packers.com/news-and-events/article-roster-moves/article-1/packers-announce-roster-moves/82a1bed1-0ef9-4e1d-895c-361b72eb4b5f|archivedate=May 4, 2018}}</ref> He made his NFL debut in the Packers' season opener against the [[Chicago Bears]]. He had four punts for 192 yards in the 24\u201323 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201809090gnb.htm |title=Chicago Bears at Green Bay Packers \u2013 September 9th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=October 5, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in his rookie season, Scott punted 71 times for 3,176 yards for a 44.73 average. Scott also had one kickoff attempt for 61 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/S/ScotJK00.htm |title=JK Scott 2018 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==NFL career statistics==\n===Regular season===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|GP !! colspan=\"18\"|Punting\n|-\n! Punts !! Yds !! Net Yds !! Lng !! Avg !! Net Avg !! Blk !! OOB !! Dn !! In 20 !! TB !! FC !! Ret !! RetY !! TD\n|-\n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] !! [[2018 Green Bay Packers season|GB]]\n| 16 || 71 || 3,176 || 2,790 || 67 || 44.7 || 38.8 || 1 || 4 || 11 || 19 || 9 || 27 || 20 || 206 || 0\n|-\n! [[2019 NFL season|2019]] !! [[2019 Green Bay Packers season|GB]]\n| 16 || 77 || 3,386 || 3,073 || 66 || 44.0 || 39.9 || 0 || 12 || 10 || 29 || 4 || 25 || 26 || 233 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total || 32 || 148 || 6,562 || 5,863 || 67 || 44.3 || 39.6 || 1 || 16 || 21 || 48 || 13 || 52 || 46 || 439 || 0\n|-\n| colspan=\"18\"|<small>Source: [http://www.nfl.com/player/j.k.scott/2560868/careerstats NFL.com]</small>\n|}\n\n===Postseason===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|GP !! colspan=\"18\"|Punting\n|-\n! Punts !! Yds !! Net Yds !! Lng !! Avg !! Net Avg !! Blk !! OOB !! Dn !! In 20 !! TB !! FC !! Ret !! RetY !! TD\n|-\n! [[2019\u201320 NFL playoffs|2019]] !! [[2019 Green Bay Packers season|GB]]\n| 2 || 8 || 345 || 309 || 62 || 43.1 || 38.6 || 0 || 2 || 2 || 2 || 0 || 2 || 2 || 36 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total || 2 || 8 || 345 || 309 || 62 || 43.1 || 38.6 || 0 || 2 || 2 || 2 || 0 || 2 || 2 || 36 || 0\n|-\n| colspan=\"18\"|<small>Source: [https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/S/ScotJK00/gamelog/post/ pro-football-reference.com]</small>\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nScott is married to Sydney Scott. They married in January 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Byington |first1=Alex |title=JK Scott out to prove his value goes beyond football |url=https://www.timesdaily.com/sports/alabama_football/jk-scott-out-to-prove-his-value-goes-beyond-football/article_f82138e4-575a-57b0-a632-d9e9f59bbdd4.html}}</ref> They have a son who was born in November 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tolentino |first1=Josh |title=Home sweet home: Packers punter JK Scott has family ties to Wisconsin |url=https://theathletic.com/662885/2018/11/20/home-sweet-home-packers-punter-jk-scott-has-family-ties-to-wisconsin/}}</ref> Scott is a [[Christianity|Christian]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hill |first1=Verne |title=FCA: GEORGIA, ALABAMA PLAYERS SHARE ABOUT THEIR PERSONAL FAITH IN CHRIST |url=https://www.wbfj.fm/fca-georgia-alabama-players-share-personal-faith-christ/}}</ref>\n\n==References==\nhttps://www.pff.com/news/nfl-2019-pff-nfl-all-pro-team\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Sports links}}\n*[https://www.packers.com/team/players-roster/jk-scott/ Green Bay Packers bio]\n*[https://rolltide.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3950 Alabama Crimson Tide bio]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sport}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Green Bay Packers|Green Bay Packers punters]]|before=[[Justin Vogel]]|years=2018\u2013present|after=incumbent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Green Bay Packers roster navbox}}\n{{2015 Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{Packers2018DraftPicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, JK}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Denver]]\n[[Category:American football punters]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football players]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football punter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name         = J. K. Scott\n| image        = JK Scott (31003782978) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size   = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = Scott in 2018\n| current_team = Green Bay Packers\n| number       = 6\n| position     = [[Punter (football)|Punter]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1995|10|30}}\n| birth_place  = [[Denver, Colorado]]\n| height_ft    = 6\n| height_in    = 6\n| weight_lbs   = 208\n| high_school  = [[Mullen High School|Mullen]] ([[Denver, Colorado]])\n| college      = [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]]\n| draftyear    = 2018\n| draftround   = 5\n| draftpick    = 172\n| pastteams    =\n* [[Green Bay Packers]] ({{NFL Year|2018}}\u2013present)\n| status       = Active\n| highlights   =\n* PFF NFL All-Pro Second Team (2019)\n* 2\u00d7 [[College Football Playoff National Championship|CFP national champion]] ([[2016 College Football Playoff National Championship|2015]], [[ 2018 College Football Playoff National Championship|2017]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2014 All-SEC football team|2014]], [[2016 All-SEC football team|2016]])\n* Second-team All-SEC ([[2017 All-SEC football team|2017]])\n| statweek      = \n| statseason    = 2019\n| statlabel1    = [[Punt (gridiron football)|Punts]]\n| statvalue1    = 148\n| statlabel2    = Punting yards\n| statvalue2    = 6,562\n| statlabel3    = Average punt\n| statvalue3    = 44.3\n| statlabel4    = Inside 20\n| statvalue4    = 48\n| statlabel5    = Longest punt\n| statvalue5    = 67\n| nflnew        = jkscott/2560868\n}}\n'''John Kimball Scott''' (born October 30, 1995) is an [[American football]] [[Punter (football)|punter]] for the [[Green Bay Packers]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]], and was selected by the Packers in the fifth round of the [[2018 NFL Draft]].\n\n==Early years==\nScott attended and played [[high school football]] at [[Mullen High School]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/Player/JK-Scott-32788/high-school-53129/ |title=JK Scott, J.K. Mullen , Kicker |website=247Sports  |access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref> He received offers from Arizona, Colorado, and Notre Dame but ultimately accepted Alabama's offer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/Recruitment/JK-Scott-34567/RecruitInterests/ |title=JK Scott Recruit Interests |website=247sports.com |access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\nScott converted 13 of 25 field goals with a long of 59 yards and 69 of 71-point after attempts during his high school career, he also had 4,758 kick off yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.maxpreps.com/m/athlete/jk-scott/HOU2jPiFEeKZ5AAmVebBJg/football/stats.htm |title=JK Scott MaxPreps Interests |website=Maxpreps.com |access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nScott attended the [[University of Alabama]], where he played on the [[Alabama Crimson Tide football]] team under head coach [[Nick Saban]] from 2014 to 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rolltide.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3950|title=Alabama Crimson Tide : JK Scott|work=RollTide.com|accessdate=May 12, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512004310/https://rolltide.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3950|archivedate=May 12, 2018}}</ref> He was a consensus first-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] selection in 2014 and was chosen as an [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] by ''[[Sporting News]]'', ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', [[ESPN]], and ''[[USA Today]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.secsports.com/article/12000565/the-2014-ap-all-sec-football-team|title=The 2014 AP All-SEC football team}}</ref> He was also named first-team All-SEC for his performances in the 2016 season, and was part of the 2015 and 2017 Alabama Crimson Tide national championship teams.\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"12\" style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Alabama Crimson Tide|color=white}};\" |'''Alabama Crimson Tide'''\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|GP !! colspan=\"15\"|Punting\n|-\n! Punts !! Yds !! Lng !! Avg !! Blk !! In 20 !! TB !! FC !! Ret !! RetY\n|-\n! [[2014 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2014]]\n| 13 || 55 || 2,640 || 73 || 48.0 || 0 || 31 || 5 || 19 || 12 || 83\n|-\n! [[2015 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2015]]\n| 15 || 70 || 3,094 || 59 || 44.2 || 1 || 25 || 9 || 18 || 27 || 279\n|-\n! [[2016 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2016]]\n| 15 || 64 || 3,020 || 66 || 47.2 || 1 || 25 || 12 || 15 || 20 || 213\n|-\n! [[2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2017]]\n| 14 || 54 || 2,320 || 64 || 43.0 || 1 || 27 || 4 || 27 || 5 || 36\n|-\n! Total || 57 || 243 || 11,074 || 73 || 45.6 || 3 || 108 || 30 || 79 || 64 || 611\n|-\n| colspan=\"12\"|<small>Source: [https://rolltide.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3950 RollTide.com]</small>\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\n[[File:JK Scott 6 Packers training camp 2019 (cropped).jpg|180px|thumb|left|Scott during 2019 training camp.]]\n{{external media\n| video1 = [http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/0ap3000000929991/packers-select-jk-scott-no-172-in-the-2018-nfl-draft Scott gets drafted by Green Bay]\n}}\n\n{{NFL predraft\n| height ft    = 6\n| height in    = 5\u215d\n| weight       = 208\n| dash         = 4.83\n| ten split    = 1.68\n| twenty split = 2.81\n| shuttle      = 4.41\n| cone drill   = 7.28\n| vertical     = 30\u00bd\n| broad ft     = 9\n| broad in     = 6\n| bench        = \n| wonderlic    = \n| arm span     = 33\u215b\n| hand span    = 9\u215b\n| note         = All values from [[2018 NFL Draft | NFL Draft]]<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.nfl.com/prospects/jk-scott?id=32462018-0002-5600-7115-5dafcb9a6922 | title = NFL Draft Prospect Profile \u2013 JK Scott | publisher = National Football League | date = March 1, 2018 | access-date = March 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.draftscout.com/ratings/pyrnotes.php?pyid=130760&draftyear=2018&genpos=P | title = Alabama P JK Scott : 2018 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile | work = NFLDraftScout.com | accessdate = May 12, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\nScott was selected by the [[Green Bay Packers]] with the 172nd overall pick in the fifth round of the [[2018 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.packers.com/news-and-events/article-draft/article-1/packers-draft-punter-jk-scott-in-fifth-round/3b71fd75-ae1b-461a-8da1-36acf4fcb21c|title=Packers draft punter JK Scott in fifth round|last=Hodkiewicz|first=Wes|work=Packers.com|date=April 28, 2018|accessdate=April 28, 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504204634/http://www.packers.com/news-and-events/article-draft/article-1/packers-draft-punter-jk-scott-in-fifth-round/3b71fd75-ae1b-461a-8da1-36acf4fcb21c|archivedate=May 4, 2018}}</ref> He was the second of four punters to be selected that year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2018/draft.htm |title=2018 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=August 10, 2018}}</ref> On May 4, 2018, he signed a contract with the Packers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.packers.com/news-and-events/article-roster-moves/article-1/packers-announce-roster-moves/82a1bed1-0ef9-4e1d-895c-361b72eb4b5f|title=Packers announce roster moves|work=Packers.com|date=May 4, 2018|accessdate=May 4, 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504204338/http://www.packers.com/news-and-events/article-roster-moves/article-1/packers-announce-roster-moves/82a1bed1-0ef9-4e1d-895c-361b72eb4b5f|archivedate=May 4, 2018}}</ref> He made his NFL debut in the Packers' season opener against the [[Chicago Bears]]. He had four punts for 192 yards in the 24\u201323 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201809090gnb.htm |title=Chicago Bears at Green Bay Packers \u2013 September 9th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=October 5, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in his rookie season, Scott punted 71 times for 3,176 yards for a 44.73 average. Scott also had one kickoff attempt for 61 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/S/ScotJK00.htm |title=JK Scott 2018 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com  |access-date=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==NFL career statistics==\n===Regular season===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|GP !! colspan=\"18\"|Punting\n|-\n! Punts !! Yds !! Net Yds !! Lng !! Avg !! Net Avg !! Blk !! OOB !! Dn !! In 20 !! TB !! FC !! Ret !! RetY !! TD\n|-\n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] !! [[2018 Green Bay Packers season|GB]]\n| 16 || 71 || 3,176 || 2,790 || 67 || 44.7 || 38.8 || 1 || 4 || 11 || 19 || 9 || 27 || 20 || 206 || 0\n|-\n! [[2019 NFL season|2019]] !! [[2019 Green Bay Packers season|GB]]\n| 16 || 77 || 3,386 || 3,073 || 66 || 44.0 || 39.9 || 0 || 12 || 10 || 29 || 4 || 25 || 26 || 233 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total || 32 || 148 || 6,562 || 5,863 || 67 || 44.3 || 39.6 || 1 || 16 || 21 || 48 || 13 || 52 || 46 || 439 || 0\n|-\n| colspan=\"18\"|<small>Source: [http://www.nfl.com/player/j.k.scott/2560868/careerstats NFL.com]</small>\n|}\n\n===Postseason===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|GP !! colspan=\"18\"|Punting\n|-\n! Punts !! Yds !! Net Yds !! Lng !!