all navbox}}\n{{Packers2018DraftPicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, JK}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Denver]]\n[[Category:American football punters]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football players]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n", "name_user": "173.25.28.114", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J._K._Scott"}
{"title_page": "Eric Thorne", "text_new": "[[File:Eric Thorne in The Merry Widow.jpg|thumb|140px|Thorne in ''The Merry Widow'']]\n'''Eric Thorne''' (1862 \u2013 26 November 1922) was an English singer and actor in [[musical theatre]] and [[comic opera]].\n\n==Life==\nIn February 1884, Thorne joined the chorus of the [[D'Oyly Carte Opera Company|D'Oyly Carte]]\u2019s touring \"A\" Company.<ref name=carte>[https://gsarchive.net/whowaswho/T/ThorneEric.htm Eric Thorne] at gsarchive.net/whowaswho, accessed 9 April 2020</ref> Later that year, the tour arrived at [[Portsea, Portsmouth#Portsea|Portsea]], and while they were there Thorne married another member of the company, Ada Doree, whose real name was Ada Earee.<ref>\u201dThorne Eric & Earee Ada Catherine E\u201d in Marriages for Portsea, vol 2b (1884), p. 840</ref>\n\nAda Doree had been born in [[Cockermouth]], [[Cumberland]], in 1850 and specialized in [[operetta]], with a focus on [[Gilbert and Sullivan]]. She had many stage credits between the 1870s and the 1890s.<ref name=eliehistory>[http://www.eliehistory.com/explore/earlsferry-house-part-2/ POTTED HISTORY No 2: Earlsferry House \u2013 Part 2 \u2013 The Glovers] at eliehistory.com</ref> \n\nIn March of 1885 Thorne briefly took the place of Walter Greyling as King Hildebrand in ''[[Princess Ida]]'', and in May took over from Hugh Seton as Sir Marmaduke Pointdextre in ''[[The Sorcerer]]'' and as Florian in ''Princess Ida''. In June 1885, ''[[H.M.S. Pinafore]]'' was added to the repertoire, and Thorne was given the part of Dick Deadeye. However, the couple\u2019s time with the D'Oyly Carte came to an end in December 1885, when Company \"A\" was closed down.<ref name=carte/>\n\nOn 29 April 1889, Thorne opened at the [[Vaudeville Theatre]] in the comic opera ''[[Faddimir]]'', singing the lead part of Faddimir the First,<ref>\u201cFaddimir, or the Triumph of Orthodoxy\u201d in ''The Theatre'', Volume 22 (Wyman & Sons, 1889), p. 335</ref> with his wife also in the company.<ref name=carte/>\n\nThorne made a name for himself in light opera and musical comedy in the West End, the provinces, and overseas, and toured France, Holland, Germany, Belgium, and the United States. He sang the part of the Toymaker in ''[[La poup\u00e9e|La Poup\u00e9e]]'' in a long run which lasted for several years. He had leading parts in ''[[The Lady Dandies]]'', ''[[The Merry Widow]]'', ''[[Les p'tites Michu|The Little Michus]]'', ''[[The Dollar Princess]]'', and ''[[The Waltz Dream]]''.<ref name=carte/>\n\nIn 1912, Thorne sang the part of Grand Duke Rutzinov in a production of [[Franz Leh\u00e1r]]'s ''[[The Count of Luxembourg]]'',<ref>[http://www.operascotland.org/tour/2726/Count-of-Luxembourg-1912 The Count of Luxembourg (1912)] at operascotland.org; W. J. MacQueen-Pope, ''Shirtfronts and sables: a story of the days when money could be spent'' (Hale, 1953), p. 59</ref> as one of the five principals, together with [[Daisy Burrell]], [[Lauri de Frece]], [[Robert Michaelis]], and Phyllis le Grand, who were collectively described by the ''Musical News'' as \"all consummate artists in their own style\".<ref>''Musical News and Herald'', vol. 42 (1912), p. 194</ref>\n\nIn 1916, Ada Doree died in London,<ref name=eliehistory> followed by Thorne in 1922.<ref name=carte/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp97993/eric-thorne Eric Thorne] at National Portrait Gallery\n*[https://theatricalia.com/person/cq9/eric-thorne Eric Thorne] at theatricalia.com\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thorne, Eric}}\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century English singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English singers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Eric Thorne in The Merry Widow.jpg|thumb|140px|Thorne in ''The Merry Widow'']]\n'''Eric Thorne''' (1862 \u2013 26 November 1922) was an English singer and actor in [[musical theatre]] and [[comic opera]].\n\n==Life==\nIn February 1884, Thorne joined the chorus of the [[D'Oyly Carte Opera Company|D'Oyly Carte]]\u2019s touring \"A\" Company.<ref name=carte>[https://gsarchive.net/whowaswho/T/ThorneEric.htm Eric Thorne] at gsarchive.net/whowaswho, accessed 9 April 2020</ref> Later that year, the tour arrived at [[Portsea, Portsmouth#Portsea|Portsea]], and while they were there Thorne married another member of the company, Ada Doree, whose real name was Ada Earee.<ref>\u201dThorne Eric & Earee Ada Catherine E\u201d in Marriages for Portsea, vol 2b (1884), p. 840</ref>\n\nAda Doree had been born in Cockermouth in 1850 and  specialized in [[operetta]], with a focus on [[Gilbert and Sullivan]]. She had many stage credits between the 1870s and the 1890s.<ref name=eliehistory>[http://www.eliehistory.com/explore/earlsferry-house-part-2/ POTTED HISTORY No 2: Earlsferry House \u2013 Part 2 \u2013 The Glovers] at eliehistory.com</ref> \n\nIn March of 1885 Thorne briefly took the place of Walter Greyling as King Hildebrand in ''[[Princess Ida]]'', and in May took over from Hugh Seton as Sir Marmaduke Pointdextre in ''[[The Sorcerer]]'' and as Florian in ''Princess Ida''. In June 1885, ''[[H.M.S. Pinafore]]'' was added to the repertoire, and Thorne was given the part of Dick Deadeye. However, the couple\u2019s time with the D'Oyly Carte came to an end in December 1885, when Company \"A\" was closed down.<ref name=carte/>\n\nOn 29 April 1889, Thorne opened at the [[Vaudeville Theatre]] in the comic opera ''[[Faddimir]]'', singing the lead part of Faddimir the First,<ref>\u201cFaddimir, or the Triumph of Orthodoxy\u201d in ''The Theatre'', Volume 22 (Wyman & Sons, 1889), p. 335</ref> with his wife also in the company.<ref name=carte/>\n\nThorne made a name for himself in light opera and musical comedy in the West End, the provinces, and overseas, and toured France, Holland, Germany, Belgium, and the United States. He sang the part of the Toymaker in ''[[La poup\u00e9e|La Poup\u00e9e]]'' in a long run which lasted for several years. He had leading parts in ''[[The Lady Dandies]]'', ''[[The Merry Widow]]'', ''[[Les p'tites Michu|The Little Michus]]'', ''[[The Dollar Princess]]'', and ''[[The Waltz Dream]]''.<ref name=carte/>\n\nIn 1912, Thorne sang the part of Grand Duke Rutzinov in a production of [[Franz Leh\u00e1r]]'s ''[[The Count of Luxembourg]]'',<ref>[http://www.operascotland.org/tour/2726/Count-of-Luxembourg-1912 The Count of Luxembourg (1912)] at operascotland.org; W. J. MacQueen-Pope, ''Shirtfronts and sables: a story of the days when money could be spent'' (Hale, 1953), p. 59</ref> as one of the five principals, together with [[Daisy Burrell]], [[Lauri de Frece]], [[Robert Michaelis]], and Phyllis le Grand, who were collectively described by the ''Musical News'' as \"all consummate artists in their own style\".<ref>''Musical News and Herald'', vol. 42 (1912), p. 194</ref>\n\nIn 1916, Ada Doree died in London,<ref name=eliehistory> followed by Thorne in 1922.<ref name=carte/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp97993/eric-thorne Eric Thorne] at National Portrait Gallery\n*[https://theatricalia.com/person/cq9/eric-thorne Eric Thorne] at theatricalia.com\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thorne, Eric}}\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century English singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English singers]]\n", "name_user": "Moonraker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Thorne"}
