n just one day|last=Bedard|first=Paul|date=May 18, 2017|website=www.washingtonexaminer.com|publisher=The Washington Examiner|accessdate=May 18, 2017}}</ref> By the end of May the RNC had raised more than $62 million in 2017. The RNC had already received more online donations than they had in the entire year of 2016.<ref name=apfund/>\n\nOn April 14, 2019, the campaign announced that it had raised $30 million in the first quarter of 2019, far outpacing the campaigns of his individual Democratic opponents in the same period. Average donations were $34.26, and nearly 99 percent of donations to the campaign were $200 or less. In addition, the Republican National Committee brought in $45.8 million in first quarter 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-trump/trumps-re-election-campaign-raised-more-than-30-million-in-first-quarter-of-2019-idUSKCN1RR00V|title=Trump's re-election campaign raised more than $30 million in first-quarter of 2019|date=April 14, 2019|accessdate=April 15, 2019|work=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable expenditures ===\nIn April 2017, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' determined that the Trump campaign had reported spending nearly $500,000 in payments to companies owned by Trump, amounting to more than 6% of the $6.3 million that the campaign reported spending.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ballhaus|first=Rebecca|date=April 17, 2017|title= Donald Trump's Companies Benefit From Campaign Funds|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trumps-companies-benefit-from-campaign-funds-1492233939|work=Wall Street Journal|location=New York City|accessdate=April 18, 2017 }}</ref> Additionally, the campaign spent more than $4 million on memorabilia (such as hats).<ref name=foxkeepamerica/>\n\nIn the third quarter of 2017, the Trump campaign spent $4.1 million (27% of its expenditures) on legal fees, including the personal legal expenses of Trump and his family.<ref name=pubinteg32017>{{cite web|url=https://www.publicintegrity.org/2017/10/15/21208/donald-trump-campaign-ramps-2020-re-election-fundraising|title=Donald Trump campaign ramps up 2020 re-election fundraising|last1=Ashley|first1=Balcerzak|last2=Levinthal|first2=Dave|date=October 15, 2017|website=www.publicintegrity.org|publisher=The Center for Public Integrity|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=cnn1017>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/10/17/politics/donald-trump-campaign-legal-fees/index.html|title=Donating to Trump? Campaign is spending $1 of every $10 on legal fees|last=Jeremy|first=Diamond|date=October 17, 2017|website=www.cnn.com|publisher=CNN|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> By this point, 10% of the campaign's overall spending since the beginning of the year had been on legal fees.<ref name=cnn1017/>\n\n{{As of|2019|March}}, Trump's campaign had spent almost twice as much on Facebook and Google ads as the entire Democratic field combined.<ref name=\"2019-03-19-axios\">{{cite web | title=Another Trump Facebook election - Axios | website=Axios | date=March 19, 2019 | url=https://www.axios.com/another-trump-facebook-election-2020-5bb5ae11-23e4-42d9-8bc3-6cfa3289f970.html | first=Sara | last=Fischer | access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn its first two years since it was launched in January 2017, the Trump 2020 campaign paid more than $890,000 in rent for space in Trump Tower,<ref>{{cite web|last=Longman|first=Martin|url=https://washingtonmonthly.com/2019/05/14/as-trump-tower-struggles-the-president-rents-office-space-to-himself/|title=As Trump Tower Struggles, the President Rents Office Space to Himself|website=Washington Monthly|date=May 14, 2019 |access-date=June 1, 2019}}</ref><ref  name=\"rent\">{{cite web|last=Alexander|first=Dan|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danalexander/2019/03/20/trump-has-now-shifted-13m-of-campaign-donor-money-into-his-business/#71e79e27aaf7|title=As Trump Tower Struggles, the President Rents Office Space to Himself|website=Forbes|date=March 20, 2019 |access-date=June 1, 2019}}</ref> and the [[Republican National Committee]] paid $225,000.<ref name=\"rent\"/>\n\n== Groups supporting Trump ==\n=== The Republican Party ===\nOn January 23, 2019, the [[Republican National Committee]], in a unanimous vote, informally endorsed the president.<ref name=\"voanews.com\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n=== Super PACs ===\nSuper PACs supporting Trump's reelection campaign include [[Ted Harvey#Stop Hillary PAC/Committee to Defend the President, Honorary Chairman and Spokesperson|Committee to Defend the President]],<ref name=cpi1/> [[Great America PAC]],<ref name=cpi1/> and [[Great America Committee]].<ref name=mikepac1>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/pence-creates-pac-ahead-2018-2020-elections-n761436|title=Pence Creates PAC Ahead of 2018, 2020 Elections|last=Hillyard|first=Vaughn|date=May 18, 2017|website=www.nbcnews.com|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=May 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=pakepac2>{{cite web|url=http://docquery.fec.gov/cgi-bin/forms/C00640664/1162693|title=Filing FEC-1162693|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=May 17, 2017|website=docquery.fec.gov|publisher=Federal Election Commission|accessdate=May 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Great America PAC]] received donations from, among others, former racer [[Walker Evans (racing driver)|Walker Evans]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docquery.fec.gov/cgi-bin/fecimg/?201705139053728781|title=Page by Page Report Display (Page 290 of 1081)|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=May 15, 2017|website=www.fec.gov|publisher=Federal Elections Commission|accessdate=May 28, 2017|quote=}}</ref> and [[Insperity]] executive Jay Mincks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docquery.fec.gov/cgi-bin/fecimg/?201705139053729066|title=Page by Page Report Display (Page 575 of 1081)|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=May 15, 2017|website=www.fec.gov|publisher=Federal Elections Commission|accessdate=May 28, 2017|quote=}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ted Harvey#Stop Hillary PAC/Committee to Defend the President, Honorary Chairman and Spokesperson|Committee to Defend the President]] super PAC received contributions from, among others, [[Enterprise Products]] executive Ralph S. Cunningham.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://docquery.fec.gov/cgi-bin/fecimg/?201705179053994618|title=Page by Page Report Display (Page 921 of 4397)|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=May 17, 2017|website=www.fec.org|publisher=Federal Elections Commission|accessdate=May 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Center for Public Integrity]] published an analysis of 2017 first-quarter federal campaign spending records which revealed that two [[Super PACs]] supporting Trump, ''Great America PAC'' and ''Committee to Defend the President'', had spent a combined $1.32 million on the 2020 election campaign.<ref name=cpi1/> [[Ted Harvey]] serves as the chairman of the Committee to Defend the President. [[Eric Beach (political consultant)|Eric Beach]] and [[Ed Rollins]] serve as co-chairmen of Great America PAC.<ref name=cpi1/> Both PACs have previously been accused by the FEC of poorly maintaining financial records, and had been threatened with penalties.<ref name=cpi1/> The Center for Public Integrity also found that several other pro-Trump PACs had already been founded in 2017, but most of them had yet to be very active. One such PAC was [[America First Action]], which was founded by the [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of a political consulting firm for which Trump's 2020 campaign treasurer is the senior vice president.<ref name=cpi1/>\n\nOn May 17, 2017, Mike Pence filed FEC paperwork to form [[Great America Committee]], a PAC that would be headed by his former campaign staffers [[Nick Ayers]] and Marty Obst.<ref name=mikepac1/><ref name=pakepac2/> This is the first time in US history that a sitting vice president has founded such a political organization.<ref name=mikepac1/>\n\nOn August 7, [[Marc Lotter]], a spokesperson for Mike Pence, confirmed to MSNBC's [[Hallie Jackson]] that the vice president had hosted Republican donors, including [[Political activities of the Koch brothers|mega-donors]] [[Charles Koch|Charles]] and [[David Koch]], at [[Number One Observatory Circle]].<ref name=standardpence2020/>\n\nAt the end of the third quarter, the FEC calculated that in 2017 super PACS and other outside groups supporting Trump had spent more than $2 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fec.gov/data/candidate/P80001571/?tab=other-spending&cycle=2020&election_full=true|title=Spending by others to support or oppose|author=<!--Not stated-->|date=n.d.|website=www.fec.gov|publisher=Federal Election Commission|accessdate=October 18, 2017|quote=Support $2,389,836.49}}</ref>\n\n====Amount spent by outside groups in support of campaign====\nTable displays the amount that groups have reported to the FEC they have spent in support of Trump's candidacy ({{as of|May 2018}})<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fec.gov/data/candidate/P80001571/?tab=other-spending&cycle=2020|title=TRUMP, DONALD J - Candidate overview - FEC.gov|website=FEC.gov}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Group\n! Amount\n|-\n|Great America PAC\n|align=right|3,152,243.73\n|-\n|The Committee to Defend the President\n|align=right|3,034,640.87\n|-\n|''Other''\n|align=right|34,558.29\n|-\n|-\n!Total\n!align=right|6,221,442.89\n|}\n\n=== Other groups ===\nIn late January 2017, several members of Trump's 2016 campaign staff formed [[America First Policies]], a pro-Trump political nonprofit. Those involved included former deputy campaign chairs [[Rick Gates (political consultant)|Rick Gates]] and [[David Bossie]]. [[Brad Parscale]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/how-facebook-ads-helped-elect-trump/|title=How Facebook ads helped elect Trump|accessdate=October 9, 2017|language=en}}</ref> and [[Katrina Pierson]] were also involved. Additionally involved were Nick Ayers and Marty Obst, both of whom served as advisors to [[Mike Pence]] during the 2016 campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2017-01-30/trump-advisers-start-america-first-policies-nonprofit|title=Trump advisers start 'America First Policies' nonprofit|last=Bykowicz|first=Julie|date=May 18, 2017|website=www.usnews.com|publisher=U.S. News & World Report|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=May 18, 2017|quote=}}</ref> Trump's former [[White House Deputy Chief of Staff|White House deputy chief of staff]] [[Katie Walsh (politician)|Katie Walsh]] has also joined the organization.<ref name=washingtonpostmeeting/> Near the end of May, members of the organization (including Walsh) participated in meetings at the RNC's D.C. offices with members Trump's family to discuss campaign strategy.<ref name=washingtonpostmeeting/><ref name=msnbcmeeting/><ref name=newsmaxmeeting/>\n\nIn 2017, Matt Braynard, a key member of Trump's 2016 campaign staff, established the organization ''Look Ahead America''.<ref name=lookahead>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmur.com/article/former-trump-campaign-staffers-to-launch-new-organization-in-nh/12165807|title=Former Trump campaign staffers to launch new organization in NH|last=Sexton|first=Adam|date=September 3, 2017|website=www.wmur.com|publisher=[[WMUR-TV]]|accessdate=August 3, 2017}}</ref> The organization has taken steps to target inactive voters in places such as New Hampshire.<ref name=lookahead/> Trump came close to winning [[2016 United States presidential election in New Hampshire|New Hampshire in the 2016 election]].<ref name=lookahead/> Look Ahead America has claimed that it will not be coordinating their efforts with the president.<ref name=lookahead/>\n\nIn August 2018, a group called the 45 Alliance was formed. All three of the group's officers had served on Trump\u2019s transition team, and two of them also served in Trump's White House. During the calendar year in which the 45 Alliance was formed, it was entirely funded by Trump for America, a nonprofit that supported [[Presidential transition of Donald Trump|Trump's transition]] ($150,000); by [[America First Policies]] ($150,000); and by the [[Republican National Committee]] ($75,000). Neil Corkery is in charge of the 45 Alliance's finances. \"He has ties to several high-profile dark money operations,\" Walker Davis wrote, \"like the Wellspring Committee and [[Judicial Crisis Network]]. In 2018, an anonymous million dollar contribution to President Trump\u2019s inauguration was linked to him.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.citizensforethics.org/tax-form-emphasizes-45-alliance-trump-ties/|title=Tax Form Emphasizes Mysterious Dark Money Group\u2019s Ties to Trump|last=Davis|first=Walker|date=2020-03-30|website=Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington (CREW)|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Rallies==\n{{main|List of post-election Donald Trump rallies}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+  2020 campaign rallies\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\" | '''Date of rally'''\n! scope=\"col\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\" | '''City'''\n! scope=\"col\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\" | '''State'''\n! scope=\"col\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\" | '''Venue'''\n! scope=\"col\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\" | '''Estimated attendance'''\n! scope=\"col\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f0f0f0;\" | '''Source'''\n|-\n|Monday, February 11, 2019\n|[[El Paso]]\n| [[Texas|TX]]\n| [[El Paso County Coliseum]]\n|6,000\n|<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tribune |first1=The Texas |last2=Samuels |first2=Alex |title=Trump falsely said El Paso was a hub of violent crime before the border fence. Now he's holding a rally there. |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2019/02/06/donald-trump-el-paso-rally-texas-feb-11/ |website=The Texas Tribune |language=en |date=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|Thursday, March 28, 2019\n|[[Grand Rapids]]\n| [[Michigan|MI]]\n| [[Van Andel Arena]]\n| 14,000\n| <ref>{{cite news |title=The Latest: Trump tells supporters 'Russia hoax is dead' |url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2019/mar/28/the-latest-trump-jr-thanks-rally-crowd-for-support/ |accessdate=1 May 2019 |work=The Washington Times |agency=AP |publisher=The Washington Times}}</ref>\n|-\n|Saturday, April 27, 2019\n|[[Green Bay, Wisconsin|Green Bay]]\n| [[Wisconsin|WI]]\n| [[Resch Center]]\n| 10,000\n| <ref>{{cite news |author1=Doug Schneider |author2=Haley BeMiller |author3=Mica Soellner |title=Donald Trump's Green Bay rally: Scenes from outside the Resch Center |url=https://www.greenbaypressgazette.com/story/news/2019/04/27/donald-trump-rally-green-bay-resch-center-scenes-ashwaubenon-brown-county-republican-politics-gop/3567255002/ |accessdate=1 May 2019 |publisher=Press Gazette Media |date=27 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|Wednesday, May 8, 2019\n|[[Panama City Beach, Florida|Panama City Beach]]\n| [[Florida|FL]]\n| [[Aaron Bessant Park Amphitheater]]\n| 7,500\n| <ref>{{cite news|last=Landler|first=Mark|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/08/us/politics/trump-rally.html|title=At Florida Rally, Trump Denounces Democrats' 'Nonsense' as He Looks to 2020|work=The New York Times|date=8 May 2019|accessdate=9 May 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|Monday, May 20, 2019\n|[[Montoursville, Pennsylvania|Montoursville]]\n| [[Pennsylvania|PA]]\n| [[Williamsport Regional Airport]]\n| 15,000\n| <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.northcentralpa.com/candidates/trump-rally-to-be-held-in-lycoming-county/article_1befb2bc-75a7-11e9-befe-73f38d9d64c5.html|title=Trump Rally to be held in Lycoming County|last=Tabb|first=Joe|date=13 May 2019|work=|accessdate=13 May 2019|publisher=NorthcentralPA.com}}</ref>\n|-\n|Tuesday, June 18, 2019\n|[[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]]\n| [[Florida|FL]]\n| [[Amway Center]]\n| 20,000\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1134559092545134593|title=I will be announcing my Second Term Presidential Run with First Lady Melania, Vice President Mike Pence, and Second Lady Karen Pence on June 18th in Orlando, Florida, at the 20,000 seat Amway Center. Join us for t